<font color="#138ce9">MAN:</font> Dan?

32
00:04:01,410 --> 00:04:02,980
Dan?

33
00:04:04,250 --> 00:04:06,050
Dan!

34
00:04:06,050 --> 00:04:09,190
Secretary would like a word.
You wanna follow me?

35
00:04:14,990 --> 00:04:17,230
<font color="#138ce9">ROBERT:</font> Well, you can say what
you want to the President.

36
00:04:17,230 --> 00:04:19,560
I've read every one
of Ellsberg's reports...

37
00:04:19,560 --> 00:04:22,400
and I'm telling you,
it's just not the case.

38
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:23,870
Dan, you know Mr. Komer.

39
00:04:25,040 --> 00:04:26,940
He's been discussing the war
with the President...

40
00:04:26,940 --> 00:04:28,440
and, well,
his sense is that we've made

41
00:04:28,440 --> 00:04:29,870
real progress
over the past year...

42
00:04:29,870 --> 00:04:31,470
but I've been doing my own
review, and it seems to me...

43
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:32,910
that things have gotten worse.

44
00:04:32,910 --> 00:04:34,010
But neither of us
have been in the field.

45
00:04:34,010 --> 00:04:35,240
You have,
you're the one who knows.

46
00:04:35,250 --> 00:04:37,480
So, what do you say?

47
00:04:37,480 --> 00:04:39,390
Are things better or worse?

48
00:04:40,920 --> 00:04:42,590
Well, Mr. Secretary...

49
00:04:42,590 --> 00:04:45,690
what I'm most impressed by is
how much things are the same.

50
00:04:45,690 --> 00:04:48,060
You see, that's exactly
what I'm saying.

51
00:04:49,730 --> 00:04:50,990
We put another
hundred thousand troops

52
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:52,860
into the field,
things are no better.

53
00:04:52,860 --> 00:04:55,330
To me, that means things
are actually worse.

54
00:04:57,740 --> 00:04:59,140
Thank you, Dan.

55
00:05:02,210 --> 00:05:03,980
- <font color="#138ce9">MAN:</font> Mr. Secretary!
- <font color="#ff00ff">(REPORTERS CLAMORING)</font>

56
00:05:04,510 --> 00:05:06,380
Mr. Secretary! Sir!

57
00:05:07,480 --> 00:05:10,580
<font color="#138ce9">ANDREWS:</font> How was
your trip, sir? Sir.

58
00:05:10,580 --> 00:05:11,920
Good afternoon, gentlemen.

59
00:05:11,920 --> 00:05:13,680
I don't have
any prepared remarks...

60
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:15,920
but I'd be very happy to take
your questions one at a time.

61
00:05:15,920 --> 00:05:17,620
- Jim.
- Mr. Secretary...

62
00:05:17,620 --> 00:05:19,020
I'm wondering
if the trip left you

63
00:05:19,020 --> 00:05:20,460
optimistic or pessimistic...

64
00:05:20,460 --> 00:05:22,890
about our prospects in this
war and our ability to win it.

65
00:05:22,900 --> 00:05:25,100
He asked whether I was
optimistic or pessimistic.

66
00:05:25,100 --> 00:05:26,630
Today, I can tell you
that military progress

67
00:05:26,630 --> 00:05:27,800
over the past 12 months...

68
00:05:27,800 --> 00:05:29,270
has exceeded our expectations.

69
00:05:29,270 --> 00:05:31,930
We're very encouraged by what
we're seeing in Vietnam.

70
00:05:31,940 --> 00:05:34,100
In every respect,
we're making progress.

71
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:35,770
And I'm especially pleased
to have had

72
00:05:35,770 --> 00:05:37,340
Bob Komer along for the trip.

73
00:05:37,340 --> 00:05:38,370
So he could see for himself

74
00:05:38,380 --> 00:05:40,010
that we've been
showing great improvement...

75
00:05:40,010 --> 00:05:41,880
in every dimension
of the war effort.

76
00:05:41,880 --> 00:05:43,880
<font color="#ff00ff">(REPORTERS CLAMORING)</font>

77
00:05:45,480 --> 00:05:46,820
Derek.

78
