ourselves to the cause...</i>

87
00:08:29,780 --> 00:08:31,710
<i>of a just
and peaceful world order</i>

88
00:08:31,720 --> 00:08:33,880
<i>through the United Nations.</i>

89
00:08:33,880 --> 00:08:35,990
<font color="#138ce9">DANIEL:</font> "May 3rd, 1950.

90
00:08:35,990 --> 00:08:37,950
"President Truman
approved $10 million

91
00:08:37,960 --> 00:08:39,890
"in military aid
to Indochina."

92
00:08:46,500 --> 00:08:48,130
<font color="#138ce9">DWIGHT EISENHOWER:</font> <i>America's leadership</i>

93
00:08:48,130 --> 00:08:49,600
<i>and prestige depend...</i>

94
00:08:49,600 --> 00:08:53,970
<i>on how we use our power in
the interests of world peace.</i>

95
00:08:53,970 --> 00:08:55,910
<font color="#138ce9">DANIEL:</font> "I feel concerned
about paragraph six...

96
00:08:55,910 --> 00:08:57,340
"which gives
authority to control

97
00:08:57,340 --> 00:08:59,280
"general elections
in Vietnam."

98
00:09:01,510 --> 00:09:03,810
<font color="#138ce9">JOHN F. KENNEDY:</font> <i>The United
States, as the world knows,</i>

99
00:09:03,820 --> 00:09:06,120
<i>will never start a war.</i>

100
00:09:06,880 --> 00:09:08,920
<font color="#138ce9">DANIEL:</font> "May 11th, 1961.

101
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:10,190
"President Kennedy orders

102
00:09:10,190 --> 00:09:11,790
"a full examination
by the Defense Department...

103
00:09:11,790 --> 00:09:15,160
"of a possible commitment
of U.S. forces to Vietnam."

104
00:09:19,230 --> 00:09:22,400
<font color="#138ce9">LYNDON JOHNSON:</font> <i>We are not
about to send American boys...</i>

105
00:09:22,400 --> 00:09:25,540
<i>9 or 10,000 miles
away from home...</i>

106
00:09:25,540 --> 00:09:29,640
<i>to do what Asian boys ought
to be doing for themselves.</i>

107
00:09:29,640 --> 00:09:32,140
"President Johnson chose to
reaffirm the Kennedy policies.

108
00:09:32,140 --> 00:09:33,980
"Military operations
should be initiated

109
00:09:33,980 --> 00:09:36,010
"under close
political control."

110
00:10:03,340 --> 00:10:04,510
<font color="#ff00ff">(GASPS)</font>

111
00:10:08,910 --> 00:10:10,180
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

112
00:10:14,150 --> 00:10:15,450
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS HEAVILY)</font>

113
00:10:21,960 --> 00:10:24,090
<font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> <font color="#ff00ff">(STUTTERING)</font>
<i>Can we just do the numbers</i>

114
00:10:24,100 --> 00:10:25,530
<i>just one more time?</i>

115
00:10:26,560 --> 00:10:28,730
The company's selling
how many shares?

116
00:10:28,730 --> 00:10:31,300
<font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> 1.35 million shares.

117
00:10:31,300 --> 00:10:33,270
And the price range is?

118
00:10:33,270 --> 00:10:36,810
Between $24.50
and $27 per share.

119
00:10:36,810 --> 00:10:38,740
Not exactly
a huge difference.

120
00:10:38,740 --> 00:10:40,880
For them.
But, you know, the bankers

121
00:10:40,880 --> 00:10:42,410
always do fiddle
with the prices.

122
00:10:42,410 --> 00:10:46,080
But for us,
that's over $3 million...

123
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:48,990
and that represents
over five years' salary

124
00:10:48,990 --> 00:10:50,890
for 25 good reporters.

125
00:10:50,890 --> 00:10:53,190
Good. But why spend
in the newsroom?

126
00:10:53,190 --> 00:10:54,760
You're far less profitable

127
00:10:54,760 --> 00:10:56,730
than Gannett
or Knight or Ridder.

128
00:10:56,730 --> 00:10:58,160
Gannett and Knight and Ridder

129
00:10:58,160 --> 00:11:01,130
own monopoly papers
in smaller cities.

130
00:11:01,130 --> 00:11:03,870
And our readers are leaders,
you know.

131
00:11:03,870 --> 00:11:05,370
They're educated.
They demand more.

132
00:11:05,370 --> 00:11:09,410
That's why we invest
in really good reporters.

133
00:11:10,040 --> 00:11:11,110
And so...

134
00:11:11,110 --> 00:11:13,810
Because quality
and profitability

135
00:11:13,810 --> 00:11:15,880
do go hand in hand.

136
00:11:15,880 --> 00:11:16,980
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

137
00:11:16,980 --> 00:11:18,250
- See?
- Yeah.

138
00:11:18,250 --> 00:11:20,650
- You know all this already.
- <font color="#ff00ff">(LAUGHS)</font> Oh, gosh!

139
00:11:20,650 --> 00:11:21,620
I don't know if I do.

140
00:11:21,620 --> 00:11:23,190
- I should get to breakfast.
- Yeah.

141
00:11:23,190 --> 00:11:24,890
We don't want Paul or Arthur
too antsy this afternoon.

142
00:11:24,890 --> 00:11:26,090
No.

143
00:11:26,090 --> 00:11:27,920
Good luck.

144
00:11:27,930 --> 00:11:29,560
- And thank you, Fritz.
- Mmm-hmm.

145
00:11:31,060 --> 00:11:32,800
- See you downtown.
- I'll see you.

146
00:11:32,800 --> 00:11:34,460
You think
this is really necessary?

147
00:11:34,470 --> 00:11:35,670
Oh, God, yes.

148
00:11:35,670 --> 00:11:39,240
Darling, you should hear how
they talk at these meetings.

149
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:40,900
It's as if
it's in a foreign language.

150
00:11:40,910 --> 00:11:43,210
No, I meant
taking the company public.

151
00:11:48,280 --> 00:11:51,780
It seems we are cash poor.

152
00:11:51,780 --> 00:11:53,280
You know, barely solvent.

153
00:11:53,280 --> 00:11:54,950
That's the newspaper business.

154
00:11:54,950 --> 00:11:56,350
That's
our newspaper business...

155
00:11:56,350 --> 00:11:57,950
and we need
the public offering

156
00:11:57,960 --> 00:12:00,160
to stay in business
and to continue to grow.

157
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:01,460
That's what Fritz says.

158
00:12:01,460 --> 00:12:03,260
And he also says
that the family

159
00:12:03,260 --> 00:12:05,500
can maintain control if we...

160
00:12:06,760 --> 00:12:08,600
Anyway, I'm just not sure
your grandfather...

161
00:12:08,600 --> 00:12:10,930
would have wanted us to
give up any control at all.

162
00:12:10,940 --> 00:12:12,340
<font color="#ff00ff">(PHONE RINGS)</font>

163
00:12:14,210 --> 00:12:16,240
- Hello?
- <font color="#138ce9">WOMAN:</font> <i>Mrs. Graham?</i>

164
00:12:16,240 --> 00:12:18,170
Yes? This is she.

165
00:12:18,180 --> 00:12:20,740
<i>Please hold
for the Chief of Staff.</i>

166
00:12:21,680 --> 00:12:22,680
Who is it?

167
00:12:23,680 --> 00:12:25,350
Haldeman.

168
00:12:25,350 --> 00:12:26,750
<font color="#138ce9">HALDEMAN:</font> <i>Mrs. Graham,
Bob Haldeman.</i>

169
00:12:26,750 --> 00:12:28,280
Yes, hello.

170
00:12:28,280 --> 00:12:31,390
<i>We've got a bit of
an issue over here.</i>

171
00:12:31,390 --> 00:12:33,050
Oh?

172
00:12:33,060 --> 00:12:34,420
<font color="#138ce9">MAN 1:</font> Well,
that makes perfect sense.

173
00:12:34,430 --> 00:12:35,990
Do you agree with that?

174
00:12:35,990 --> 00:12:37,960
<font color="#138ce9">MAN 2:</font> Without a doubt.

175
00:12:37,960 --> 00:12:39,860
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHATTERING CONTINUES)</font>

176
00:12:41,600 --> 00:12:42,830
<font color="#ff00ff">(BREATHING HEAVILY)</font>

177
00:12:44,840 --> 00:12:46,270
Oh, Jesus.

178
00:12:47,510 --> 00:12:49,200
I'm so sorry.

179
00:12:49,210 --> 00:12:50,870
- Sorry, sorry, sorry.
- Good morning.

180
00:12:50,880 --> 00:12:55,980
So late. I had to get all this
stuff together...

181
00:12:55,980 --> 00:12:58,080
and then I had
an unexpected call.

182
00:12:58,080 --> 00:13:00,980
Well, what is
with the suitcase?

183
00:13:00,980 --> 00:13:04,120
Ben, I told you,
this is the day.

184
00:13:04,120 --> 00:13:05,520
We're meeting
with the bankers today.

185
00:13:05,520 --> 00:13:08,090
- Oh, yes. Right, right.
- You know this.

186
00:13:08,090 --> 00:13:09,790
I bet you every dollar
in my wallet

187
00:13:09,790 --> 00:13:10,930
that you are
the only person...

188
00:13:10,930 --> 00:13:13,360
in that boardroom who's read
through all that nonsense.

189
00:13:13,360 --> 00:13:16,100
<font color="#ff00ff">(LAUGHS)</font> I'm probably
the only one who needs to.

190
00:13:16,100 --> 00:13:18,930
What do you think
of Neil Sheehan?

191
00:13:18,940 --> 00:13:20,940
Oh, gosh,
his coverage of Vietnam

192
00:13:20,940 --> 00:13:22,670
is just absolutely marvelous.

193
00:13:22,670 --> 00:13:23,810
Why?

194
00:13:23,810 --> 00:13:26,240
You thinking of trying to
steal him from <i>The Times?</i>

195
00:13:26,240 --> 00:13:27,740
I'm not sure
we can afford him.

196
00:13:27,740 --> 00:13:30,950
He... He hasn't had
a piece in three months.

197
00:13:30,950 --> 00:13:32,310
Oh?

198
00:13:32,320 --> 00:13:34,420
Do you think
he's onto something?

199
00:13:34,420 --> 00:13:36,690
Well, I saw Abe
at a dinner party last week

200
00:13:36,690 --> 00:13:40,290
and he was looking
mighty, mighty smug.

201
00:13:40,290 --> 00:13:42,790
Doesn't he always? <font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font>

202
00:13:42,790 --> 00:13:43,930
So who was it?

203
00:13:43,930 --> 00:13:45,060
Who was what?

204
00:13:45,060 --> 00:13:47,200
Your unexpected call.

205
00:13:47,200 --> 00:13:50,270
<font color="#ff00ff">(GASPS)</font> Oh, I buried the lede.

206
00:13:50,270 --> 00:13:52,200
The White House.

207
00:13:52,200 --> 00:13:54,170
- Haldeman rang.
- Yeah?

208
00:13:54,170 --> 00:13:56,370
It seems
the President has decided

209
00:13:56,370 --> 00:13:58,240
not to provide Judith...

210
00:13:58,240 --> 00:14:00,310
with credentials
to cover the Nixon wedding.

211
00:14:00,310 --> 00:14:02,340
- Jesus Christ.
- Yeah.

212
00:14:02,350 --> 00:14:04,580
They said we could
send another reporter.

213
00:14:04,580 --> 00:14:07,250
- Oh, yeah? Can't believe that.
- <font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

214
00:14:07,250 --> 00:14:08,980
I know, I know.

215
00:14:08,990 --> 00:14:10,350
- But...
- But what?

216
00:14:10,350 --> 00:14:11,590
I'm not sure I entirely blame

217
00:14:11,590 --> 00:14:13,460
the President
on this one, Ben.

218
00:14:13,460 --> 00:14:14,660
No?

219
00:14:14,660 --> 00:14:16,630
Would you want Judith to cover
your daughter's wedding?

220
00:14:16,630 --> 00:14:18,330
Well, my daughter's
only 10 years old...

221
00:14:18,330 --> 00:14:20,060
I think she burned her bridges

222
00:14:20,060 --> 00:14:22,170
when she
crashed Julie's reception.

223
00:14:22,170 --> 00:14:23,770
- They're being punitive.
- Her pen is so sharp.

224
00:14:23,770 --> 00:14:25,170
- Of course it's punitive.
- This is punitive.

225
00:14:25,170 --> 00:14:27,440
Of course it's punitive.

226
00:14:27,440 --> 00:14:31,440
She compared Tricia Nixon
to a vanilla ice cream cone.

227
00:14:31,440 --> 00:14:33,780
- <font color="#ff00ff">(LAUGHS)</font> Yeah, she did.
- Yeah.

228
00:14:33,780 --> 00:14:35,610
I mean, why would
her father want Judy

229
00:14:35,610 --> 00:14:37,180
to cover
his daughter's wedding?

230
00:14:37,180 --> 00:14:38,680
Oh, come on.

231
00:14:38,680 --> 00:14:39,980
I just...

232
00:14:39,980 --> 00:14:43,620
Are you sure we're striking
the right tone here, Ben?

233
00:14:43,620 --> 00:14:45,020
Oh, we're gonna
do this again?

234
00:14:45,020 --> 00:14:46,990
No. Uh,
the New Style section.

235
00:14:46,990 --> 00:14:50,460
Sometimes that stiletto party
coverage can be a little mean.

236
00:14:50,460 --> 00:14:52,430
I'm handling it.
I'm looking for a new editor.

237
00:14:52,430 --> 00:14:53,730
Yes, are you?
Because I know

238
00:14:53,730 --> 00:14:56,200
I've talked to you
about this before.

239
00:14:56,200 --> 00:14:59,740
You are losing
female readership, you know.

240
00:14:59,740 --> 00:15:01,400
And I think you might
want to focus more

241
00:15:01,400 --> 00:15:02,540
on what women read...

242
00:15:02,540 --> 00:15:05,510
Katharine, keep your finger
outta my eye.

243
00:15:12,380 --> 00:15:13,780
You... <font color="#ff00ff">(INHALES)</font>

244
00:15:13,780 --> 00:15:15,590
<font color="#ff00ff">(HUMMING)</font>

245
00:15:16,720 --> 00:15:18,820
These breakfasts
were your idea, you know.

246
00:15:18,820 --> 00:15:22,390
Yes. And you are the publisher
and you are my boss.

247
00:15:22,390 --> 00:15:24,160
And I, uh...
I value the input,

248
00:15:24,160 --> 00:15:26,400
but I... I heard you
the first three times.

249
00:15:26,400 --> 00:15:29,200
You know, I just think
there might be another way...

250
00:15:29,200 --> 00:15:31,430
that we could cool it with
the White House.

251
00:15:31,440 --> 00:15:34,640
Maybe we could just send
somebody else, you know...

252
00:15:34,640 --> 00:15:37,310
Nope, nope. Nope. I'm not
gonna send another reporter.

253
00:15:37,310 --> 00:15:39,280
Because it's not
hard news, Ben.

254
00:15:39,280 --> 00:15:40,610
It's just a wedding.

255
00:15:40,610 --> 00:15:42,380
It's not just a wedding.

256
00:15:42,380 --> 00:15:43,450
It's a wedding of the daughter

257
00:15:43,450 --> 00:15:45,150
of the President
of the United States.

258
00:15:45,150 --> 00:15:46,680
Why not let that girl
have her day?

259
00:15:46,680 --> 00:15:48,320
And we can't have
an administration

260
00:15:48,320 --> 00:15:49,550
dictating to us
our coverage...

261
00:15:49,550 --> 00:15:50,790
just because they don't like

262
00:15:50,790 --> 00:15:53,690
what we print about them
in our newspaper.

263
00:15:55,660 --> 00:15:56,790
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font>

264
00:15:58,160 --> 00:16:00,300
Wonder if Abe
cares so passionately

265
00:16:00,300 --> 00:16:02,400
about who covers
the wedding for his paper.

266
00:16:02,400 --> 00:16:04,400
I don't give a rat's ass
what Abe or anybody

267
00:16:04,400 --> 00:16:06,070
at <i>The New York Times</i>
cares about.

268
00:16:06,070 --> 00:16:07,600
Not true.
I give one rat's ass.

269
00:16:07,600 --> 00:16:09,670
- <font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font> Yeah.
- One retromingent...

270
00:16:09,670 --> 00:16:11,510
- rat's ass.
- <font color="#ff00ff">(BOTH LAUGH)</font>

271
00:16:35,030 --> 00:16:37,100
<font color="#ff00ff">(NEWSROOM CHATTERING)</font>

272
00:16:37,100 --> 00:16:38,370
<font color="#138ce9">MAN:</font> Well, it's real important.

273
00:16:38,370 --> 00:16:40,770
Can you get him for me?

274
00:16:40,770 --> 00:16:44,140
Tell them it's from Sheehan.
Don't walk.

275
00:16:45,410 --> 00:16:47,010
<font color="#ff00ff">(TRAFFIC NOISES)</font>

276
00:16:51,250 --> 00:16:53,080
<font color="#ff00ff">(CAR HORNS HONKING)</font>

277
00:16:56,150 --> 00:16:57,390
<font color="#ff00ff">(BRAKES SCREECH)</font>

278
00:17:00,260 --> 00:17:01,730
<font color="#ff00ff">(PANTING)</font>

279
00:17:11,270 --> 00:17:12,640
It's from Sheehan.

280
00:17:15,340 --> 00:17:17,670
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIREN BLARING OUTSIDE)</font>

281
00:17:19,510 --> 00:17:21,550
Abe, here it is.

282
00:17:38,430 --> 00:17:39,660
<font color="#138ce9">HOWARD:</font> <i>Okay,
Broder's got Nixon</i>

283
00:17:39,660 --> 00:17:41,800
<i>working on his second term.</i>

284
00:17:41,800 --> 00:17:45,000
<i>Osnos has something on G.I.s
buying heroin in Saigon...</i>

285
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:47,600
but Ryder's got
a rocket on the FBI list

286
00:17:47,600 --> 00:17:48,800
of potential subversives.

287
00:17:48,810 --> 00:17:50,370
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Save it for the afternoon.

288
00:17:50,370 --> 00:17:52,470
I need Chal and Judith.

289
00:17:52,480 --> 00:17:53,780
<font color="#138ce9">HOWARD:</font> Judith!

290
00:17:53,780 --> 00:17:55,980
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Is that real,
the subversives list?

291
00:17:55,980 --> 00:17:58,310
Oh, yeah. Hoover
and Justice keep a copy.

292
00:17:58,320 --> 00:17:59,610
Thousands of names.

293
00:17:59,620 --> 00:18:01,280
Geyelin heard the White House
is shutting Judith out.

294
00:18:01,290 --> 00:18:02,350
Yeah, I'm working on that.

295
00:18:02,350 --> 00:18:03,720
We think editorial
should run something.

296
00:18:03,720 --> 00:18:05,350
I just heard somebody say
they're working on that.

297
00:18:05,360 --> 00:18:06,420
Well, if the White House is

298
00:18:06,420 --> 00:18:07,520
gonna take
a stance like that...

299
00:18:07,530 --> 00:18:10,030
don't you think
we should plant a flag?

300
00:18:12,160 --> 00:18:16,200
Did you see Sheehan at the
Kissinger press conference?

301
00:18:16,200 --> 00:18:17,370
<font color="#138ce9">BAGDIKIAN:</font> No.

302
00:18:17,370 --> 00:18:19,130
What about the Al Haig thing?

303
00:18:19,140 --> 00:18:21,140
No, <i>Times</i> sent the new kid.

304
00:18:21,870 --> 00:18:23,310
The new kid, huh?

305
00:18:23,310 --> 00:18:25,370
You think Sheehan's
onto something.

306
00:18:25,380 --> 00:18:26,940
Yeah.

307
00:18:26,940 --> 00:18:29,480
Well, Neil has been known
to disappear.

308
00:18:29,480 --> 00:18:32,350
No, no. I'm telling you,
he has something.

309
00:18:32,350 --> 00:18:34,550
You want me to do
a little digging?

310
00:18:34,550 --> 00:18:37,220
No, that's below
your pay grade.

311
00:18:37,220 --> 00:18:38,560
Intern!

312
00:18:39,520 --> 00:18:42,220
You working on anything
important, chief?

313
00:18:42,230 --> 00:18:44,630
Uh, no, Mr. Bradlee.

314
00:18:44,630 --> 00:18:47,160
Well, everything we do
is important at <i>The Post.</i>

315
00:18:47,160 --> 00:18:48,560
Yeah. That's $40.

316
00:18:48,570 --> 00:18:51,630
I want you to take the
first train up to New York...

317
00:18:51,640 --> 00:18:53,440
and go to
<i>The Times</i> building on 43rd.

318
00:18:53,440 --> 00:18:54,640
Don't tell them
who you work for...

319
00:18:54,640 --> 00:18:57,310
but find a reporter
by the name of Sheehan.

320
00:18:57,310 --> 00:18:58,870
Uh, Neil Sheehan?

321
00:18:58,880 --> 00:19:03,510
Yeah, yeah, find out what
Neil Sheehan is working on.

322
00:19:04,280 --> 00:19:06,110
Is that legal?

323
00:19:06,120 --> 00:19:09,790
Well, what is it you think we
do here for a living, kid?

324
00:19:09,790 --> 00:19:11,290
Get a receipt for the tickets.

325
00:19:11,290 --> 00:19:12,290
Yeah.

326
00:19:19,960 --> 00:19:20,960
<font color="#ff00ff">(ELEVATOR DINGS)</font>

327
00:19:24,030 --> 00:19:25,200
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

328
00:19:28,510 --> 00:19:30,980
- <font color="#138ce9">MAN:</font> Morning, Mrs. Graham.
- Hello, morning.

329
00:19:32,140 --> 00:19:34,640
<font color="#ff00ff">(INDISTINCT CHATTER)</font>

330
00:19:34,650 --> 00:19:36,710
<font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> Hello.
Morning, everybody.

331
00:19:36,710 --> 00:19:38,050
- Hi, Oz.
- Mrs. Graham.

332
00:19:38,050 --> 00:19:39,280
Morning, Arthur.

333
00:19:40,580 --> 00:19:42,190
Hello. Hello, everyone.

334
00:19:44,720 --> 00:19:46,590
So, everyone's here.

335
00:19:46,590 --> 00:19:49,360
- Hello, Ray. My Galahad.
- Good morning.

336
00:19:49,360 --> 00:19:50,900
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font> Thank you.

337
00:19:51,460 --> 00:19:52,800
<font color="#ff00ff">(CLEARS THROAT)</font>

338
00:20:02,210 --> 00:20:03,540
And I used to be the only one

339
00:20:03,540 --> 00:20:05,470
who brought
his homework to class.

340
00:20:05,480 --> 00:20:07,740
<font color="#ff00ff">(LAUGHTER)</font>

341
00:20:07,750 --> 00:20:10,550
I think we're all here.
Should we get started?

342
00:20:10,550 --> 00:20:11,950
Didn't you crash the wedding

343
00:20:11,950 --> 00:20:14,250
of Nixon's other daughter
to get a story?

344
00:20:14,250 --> 00:20:17,050
Well, I did get a story but I
didn't crash Julie's wedding.

345
00:20:17,050 --> 00:20:19,120
No, just the reception
afterwards, right?

346
00:20:19,120 --> 00:20:20,350
There is a distinction.

347
00:20:20,360 --> 00:20:21,460
Not to
the father of the bride.

348
00:20:21,460 --> 00:20:22,760
He's paying per plate.

349
00:20:22,760 --> 00:20:24,530
I think the American people
are paying per plate.

350
00:20:24,530 --> 00:20:26,060
<font color="#138ce9">HOWARD:</font> Wait, let's do
a story about that.

351
00:20:26,060 --> 00:20:28,500
- Yeah, let's...
- Judith should crash again.

352
00:20:28,500 --> 00:20:29,730
I didn't crash
Julie's wedding.

353
00:20:29,730 --> 00:20:31,030
What would you
call it, Judith?

354
00:20:31,040 --> 00:20:32,870
Well, I would call it
deft reportage.

355
00:20:32,870 --> 00:20:34,500
All right, come on,
come on, everybody.

356
00:20:34,510 --> 00:20:37,640
How are we gonna cover
this Nixon-Cox wedding?

357
00:20:41,980 --> 00:20:43,950
Uh... Who else
is gonna be there?

358
00:20:43,950 --> 00:20:45,410
- Here.
- Judith's got the guest list.

359
00:20:45,410 --> 00:20:47,280
No, I mean of
the other press.

360
00:20:47,280 --> 00:20:50,290
<i>The Times, the Sun, the Globe,</i>
all the international papers.

361
00:20:50,290 --> 00:20:51,950
All right.

362
00:20:51,950 --> 00:20:55,630
So, we call them,
we call all of them...

363
00:20:56,560 --> 00:20:59,460
and we say Nixon
has shut us out...

364
00:20:59,460 --> 00:21:02,160
and then we ask them
for their notes.

365
00:21:02,160 --> 00:21:04,570
Ben, there's no way in hell
anyone's gonna give me a fill.

366
00:21:04,570 --> 00:21:07,500
No, it'll be
an act of solidarity.

367
00:21:07,510 --> 00:21:10,010
They'll be defending
the First Amendment.

368
00:21:10,010 --> 00:21:11,840
We'll tell them
that the only way

369
00:21:11,840 --> 00:21:13,780
to protect
the right to publish...

370
00:21:13,780 --> 00:21:15,980
is to publish.

371
00:21:21,180 --> 00:21:22,490
I don't understand.

372
00:21:22,490 --> 00:21:25,290
You said
we'd set the price at $27.

373
00:21:25,290 --> 00:21:26,850
No, we said there was a range.

374
00:21:26,860 --> 00:21:29,620
And the demand on the
road show was soft.

375
00:21:29,630 --> 00:21:32,760
Why not set it at $26?
Or $25 even?

376
00:21:32,760 --> 00:21:34,660
Well, Paul, we feel
that setting the price

377
00:21:34,660 --> 00:21:36,730
at $24.50 would be
more prudent.

378
00:21:36,730 --> 00:21:38,170
It's just a couple bucks.

379
00:21:38,170 --> 00:21:40,040
It's not just
a couple of bucks.

380
00:21:40,040 --> 00:21:42,810
It's 1.35 million shares...

381
00:21:43,210 --> 00:21:44,980
so it is...

382
00:21:46,440 --> 00:21:48,280
Three million.

383
00:21:48,280 --> 00:21:52,650
Over $3 million less.
That's a lot to a newspaper.

384
00:21:52,650 --> 00:21:54,550
How many reporters is that?

385
00:21:54,550 --> 00:21:55,650
It's 25.

386
00:21:55,650 --> 00:21:57,020
Let's not get bogged down.

387
00:21:57,020 --> 00:21:58,450
<font color="#138ce9">PAUL:</font> It has to be quite a few.

388
00:21:58,460 --> 00:22:00,060
<font color="#138ce9">ARTHUR:</font> At least a dozen. Fritz?

389
00:22:01,630 --> 00:22:03,260
It's 25 reporters.

390
00:22:03,260 --> 00:22:05,430
Twenty-five reporters.

391
00:22:05,430 --> 00:22:06,700
Twenty-five reporters.

392
00:22:06,700 --> 00:22:08,830
Gentlemen,
we know it's not ideal...

393
00:22:08,830 --> 00:22:10,170
but a few of our investors

394
00:22:10,170 --> 00:22:13,470
balked at the nature
of the company.

395
00:22:13,470 --> 00:22:14,700
They don't like newspapers?

396
00:22:14,700 --> 00:22:17,470
They like Gannett and
Knight and Ridder...

397
00:22:17,480 --> 00:22:18,670
but frankly they're concerned

398
00:22:18,680 --> 00:22:21,280
about your ability
to turn a serious profit.

399
00:22:34,960 --> 00:22:36,290
Gannett and Knight and Ridder

400
00:22:36,290 --> 00:22:38,190
own monopoly papers
in smaller markets.

401
00:22:38,190 --> 00:22:40,430
That's why
they're more profitable.

402
00:22:40,430 --> 00:22:43,670
The whole point of the
offering is to grow...

403
00:22:43,670 --> 00:22:45,830
while investing in the quality
of the paper.

404
00:22:45,840 --> 00:22:49,200
Kay and I have talked
a great deal about this...

405
00:22:49,210 --> 00:22:52,210
and we believe
that improving quality...

406
00:22:52,210 --> 00:22:55,850
will naturally lead to
greater profitability.

407
00:22:57,610 --> 00:22:58,850
Unfortunate.

408
00:22:58,850 --> 00:23:00,850
It's more than unfortunate.

409
00:23:00,850 --> 00:23:02,620
Doesn't this happen
all the time?

410
00:23:02,620 --> 00:23:05,890
Bankers lowering the price for
their institutional investors.

411
00:23:05,890 --> 00:23:07,560
Fritz, isn't this
what we discussed?

412
00:23:07,560 --> 00:23:08,720
I think the family
should consider

413
00:23:08,730 --> 00:23:09,890
giving up some control.

414
00:23:09,890 --> 00:23:12,090
- Maybe another board seat.
- Absolutely not.

415
00:23:12,100 --> 00:23:14,600
This isn't a surprise, Fritz.
Ever since Phil's accident...

416
00:23:14,600 --> 00:23:15,730
<font color="#138ce9">FRITZ:</font> Arthur.

417
00:23:15,730 --> 00:23:18,200
No offense, Kay.
It's unfortunate...

418
00:23:18,200 --> 00:23:19,900
but the buyers
are obviously skittish

419
00:23:19,900 --> 00:23:21,340
about having
a woman in charge...

420
00:23:21,340 --> 00:23:23,540
and it's not like
it's an easy sell.

421
00:23:23,540 --> 00:23:26,680
It's a local paper with modest
margins, modest ambitions.

422
00:23:26,680 --> 00:23:28,110
<font color="#138ce9">PAUL:</font> I think Mr. Bradlee
would take issue

423
00:23:28,110 --> 00:23:29,380
with that characterization.

424
00:23:29,380 --> 00:23:31,350
<font color="#138ce9">ARTHUR:</font> Sure, she pads
his budget every year.

425
00:23:31,350 --> 00:23:33,110
Call my office.
Tell them I'm going to

426
00:23:33,120 --> 00:23:35,020
miss my lunch at Occidental.

427
00:23:35,020 --> 00:23:36,920
Another dozen reporters.
For what?

428
00:23:36,920 --> 00:23:38,690
To nip at the heels
of <i>The Times?</i>

429
00:23:38,690 --> 00:23:39,850
So we can pretend like

430
00:23:39,860 --> 00:23:41,860
we're even remotely
in the same league?

431
00:23:41,860 --> 00:23:44,230
Make it a five o'clock drink
at the Jefferson.

432
00:23:44,230 --> 00:23:46,330
<font color="#138ce9">FRITZ:</font> Arthur, Kay was right.
Lazard is just trying...

433
00:23:46,330 --> 00:23:47,590
to cut a better deal
by squeezing us.

434
00:23:47,600 --> 00:23:48,760
<font color="#138ce9">ARTHUR:</font> Come on, Fritz.

435
00:23:48,770 --> 00:23:49,830
Why do you think that is?

436
00:23:49,830 --> 00:23:51,030
<font color="#138ce9">FRITZ:</font> Because they're bankers.

437
00:23:51,040 --> 00:23:52,600
<font color="#138ce9">ARTHUR:</font> Which is why
they want more control.

438
00:23:52,600 --> 00:23:53,740
They want assurances

439
00:23:53,740 --> 00:23:54,870
that she's not
gonna squander it all.

440
00:23:54,870 --> 00:23:56,640
I mean, come on.

441
00:23:56,640 --> 00:23:59,040
Fritz, Kay throws
a great party...

442
00:23:59,040 --> 00:24:01,880
but her father gave the paper
to her husband.

443
00:24:01,880 --> 00:24:03,610
The only reason
she's running things

444
00:24:03,610 --> 00:24:05,980
is because he...
Because Phil died.

445
00:24:07,180 --> 00:24:10,950
Don't get me wrong,
I think she is a lovely woman.

446
00:24:10,950 --> 00:24:12,820
But she got rid
of Al Friendly...

447
00:24:12,820 --> 00:24:14,290
and brought in a pirate

448
00:24:14,290 --> 00:24:16,960
who does nothing
but bleed our margins.

449
00:24:16,960 --> 00:24:18,630
I mean, you can't be surprised

450
00:24:18,630 --> 00:24:19,860
that the buyers
are concerned...

451
00:24:19,860 --> 00:24:21,100
that she doesn't have
the resolve

452
00:24:21,100 --> 00:24:23,070
to turn a serious profit.

453
00:24:28,470 --> 00:24:30,840
Kay, it's your decision...

454
00:24:30,840 --> 00:24:32,970
but in my opinion,
if you want this

455
00:24:32,980 --> 00:24:35,240
to be more than
a little family paper...

456
00:24:35,250 --> 00:24:38,520
it has to be more than
a little family business.

457
00:24:41,690 --> 00:24:44,420
Thank you, Arthur,
for your frankness.

458
00:24:45,660 --> 00:24:47,020
All right.

459
00:24:48,290 --> 00:24:49,390
We're set?

460
00:24:49,390 --> 00:24:51,360
<font color="#138ce9">LIZ:</font> All set, Mr. Parsons.

461
00:24:53,760 --> 00:24:55,300
- Accident...
- <font color="#ff00ff">(DOOR CLOSES)</font>

462
00:24:57,270 --> 00:24:58,500
<font color="#ff00ff">(STUTTERS)</font>

463
00:24:58,500 --> 00:25:00,240
It wasn't an accident.

464
00:25:01,340 --> 00:25:02,570
Phil's suicide.

465
00:25:02,570 --> 00:25:06,940
I don't know why people insist
on calling it an accident.

466
00:25:08,110 --> 00:25:10,650
Is it to make them
feel better?

467
00:25:11,750 --> 00:25:14,950
Or do they think
they're being kind?

468
00:25:14,950 --> 00:25:17,150
I don't know, I don't know.

469
00:25:17,850 --> 00:25:20,020
So, do you think I should

470
00:25:20,020 --> 00:25:22,660
give up more seats
on the board?

471
00:25:22,660 --> 00:25:24,530
Of course not.

472
00:25:25,960 --> 00:25:28,230
We're going to be fine.

473
00:25:28,230 --> 00:25:29,700
Hmm.

474
00:25:29,700 --> 00:25:32,600
This passage
in the prospectus,

475
00:25:32,600 --> 00:25:35,240
I read it earlier today.

476
00:25:38,910 --> 00:25:41,510
Oh, yes.

