00:45:35,500 --> 00:45:36,870
- <font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Great stuff.
- <font color="#138ce9">HOWARD:</font> And get this.

941
00:45:36,870 --> 00:45:38,310
He changes the mission

942
00:45:38,310 --> 00:45:40,410
from base security
to active combat.

943
00:45:40,410 --> 00:45:42,340
- My God.
- It's a huge shift.

944
00:45:42,350 --> 00:45:43,880
He's widening the war.

945
00:45:43,880 --> 00:45:45,550
But he insists on secrecy.

946
00:45:45,550 --> 00:45:47,180
The American people are
not to be told.

947
00:45:47,180 --> 00:45:48,650
All right, okay.
So this is the real deal...

948
00:45:48,650 --> 00:45:50,450
so how long
till you can write it up?

949
00:45:50,450 --> 00:45:52,120
I can have it for Thursday.

950
00:45:52,120 --> 00:45:53,250
Well, what if we pretend

951
00:45:53,260 --> 00:45:55,460
you're a reporter,
not a novelist?

952
00:45:55,460 --> 00:45:56,960
Uh, I suppose I could pull

953
00:45:56,960 --> 00:45:58,390
something together
by tomorrow night.

954
00:45:58,390 --> 00:46:00,400
Okay, we can
run it on Wednesday.

955
00:46:01,560 --> 00:46:03,330
<font color="#138ce9">MURREY:</font> I know
we need to get this out, Ben,

956
00:46:03,330 --> 00:46:04,770
but I'd like to
spend a minute...

957
00:46:04,770 --> 00:46:07,170
going through what we've got
on Rolling Thunder.

958
00:46:07,170 --> 00:46:08,740
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Go through
all the research you want...

959
00:46:08,740 --> 00:46:10,500
but so help me God,
if we don't have

960
00:46:10,510 --> 00:46:12,140
these pages
by tomorrow night...

961
00:46:12,140 --> 00:46:13,440
we might as well
not have them at all.

962
00:46:13,440 --> 00:46:14,510
Too late.

963
00:46:15,710 --> 00:46:16,780
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> What?

964
00:46:16,780 --> 00:46:18,180
<i>Times</i> already has it.

965
00:46:22,120 --> 00:46:23,450
Well, of course they have it.

966
00:46:23,450 --> 00:46:25,720
"President Johnson
decided on April 1, 1965..."

967
00:46:25,720 --> 00:46:28,460
Of course <i>The Times</i> had...
Written by Neil Sheehan.

968
00:46:28,460 --> 00:46:31,090
"...because
a month of bombing..."

969
00:46:31,090 --> 00:46:32,490
<font color="#138ce9">NIXON:</font> <i>Neil Sheehan's a bastard.</i>

970
00:46:32,500 --> 00:46:33,960
<i>He's been a bastard for years.</i>

971
00:46:33,960 --> 00:46:35,830
<font color="#138ce9">EHRLICHMAN:</font> <i>Mr. President,
the Attorney General</i>

972
00:46:35,830 --> 00:46:37,230
<i>has called a couple times...</i>

973
00:46:37,230 --> 00:46:40,170
<i>about these</i>
New York Times <i>stories.</i>

974
00:46:40,170 --> 00:46:41,900
<font color="#138ce9">NIXON:</font> <i>You mean to
prosecute</i> The Times?

975
00:46:41,900 --> 00:46:43,340
<i>Hell, my view is</i>

976
00:46:43,340 --> 00:46:45,240
<i>to prosecute the goddamn
pricks that gave it to 'em.</i>

977
00:46:45,240 --> 00:46:46,340
<font color="#138ce9">EHRLICHMAN:</font> <i>If you can
find out who that is.</i>

978
00:46:46,340 --> 00:46:47,470
<font color="#138ce9">NIXON:</font> <i>Yeah, I know.</i>

979
00:46:47,480 --> 00:46:49,310
<i>I mean, could</i> The Times
<i>be prosecuted?</i>

980
00:46:49,310 --> 00:46:51,380
<font color="#138ce9">EHRLICHMAN:</font> <i>Apparently so.</i>

981
00:46:51,380 --> 00:46:52,550
<font color="#138ce9">NIXON:</font> <i>As far as</i>
The Times <i>is concerned,</i>

982
00:46:52,550 --> 00:46:53,880
<i>hell, they're our enemies.</i>

983
00:46:53,880 --> 00:46:56,650
<i>I think we just oughta do it.</i>

984
00:46:56,650 --> 00:46:58,590
Son of a bitch.

985
00:47:01,760 --> 00:47:02,920
Abe Rosenthal.

986
00:47:02,930 --> 00:47:05,690
Good evening. Their table
is right over there, sir.

987
00:47:07,260 --> 00:47:09,260
<font color="#138ce9">ABE:</font> Brownell and Loeb over
at Lord Day and Lord...

988
00:47:09,270 --> 00:47:12,630
told Punch in no uncertain
terms not to publish.

989
00:47:12,630 --> 00:47:14,800
Only after Scotty Reston
threatened

990
00:47:14,800 --> 00:47:16,400
to publish
in the <i>Vineyard Gazette...</i>

991
00:47:16,400 --> 00:47:18,040
did Punch decide to print.

992
00:47:18,040 --> 00:47:20,570
Wouldn't have had
quite the same impact.

993
00:47:20,580 --> 00:47:21,670
<font color="#ff00ff">(LAUGHING)</font>

994
00:47:21,680 --> 00:47:22,680
Jimmy.

995
00:47:24,550 --> 00:47:28,720
We've been asked to refrain
from further publication...

996
00:47:28,720 --> 00:47:30,850
by the Attorney General.

997
00:47:32,250 --> 00:47:34,760
Nixon's taking us to court?

998
00:47:40,830 --> 00:47:42,530
Kay, I'm sorry...

999
00:47:42,530 --> 00:47:43,800
Oh, no.

1000
00:47:45,700 --> 00:47:46,770
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1001
00:47:47,540 --> 00:47:48,670
Gosh.

1002
00:47:50,110 --> 00:47:51,870
<font color="#ff00ff">(BREATHES DEEPLY)</font>

1003
00:47:53,410 --> 00:47:55,270
Why don't I go get the check?

1004
00:47:55,280 --> 00:47:56,780
No, sit tight,
don't argue with me.

1005
00:47:56,780 --> 00:47:58,720
I'll be right back.

1006
00:48:03,890 --> 00:48:06,350
Mr. Rosenthal
had to leave on business.

1007
00:48:06,360 --> 00:48:08,250
Certainly,
we'll put it on his tab.

1008
00:48:08,260 --> 00:48:09,490
No, I'll take the bill,

1009
00:48:09,490 --> 00:48:12,230
but could I trouble you
to use your telephone?

1010
00:48:12,230 --> 00:48:13,660
But of course, madam.

1011
00:48:21,370 --> 00:48:23,470
There's a fella I overlapped
with at RAND.

1012
00:48:23,470 --> 00:48:25,570
He was a bit of
a showboat, but smart.

1013
00:48:25,570 --> 00:48:27,270
And he worked for McNamara...

1014
00:48:27,280 --> 00:48:28,510
and he had opinions

1015
00:48:28,510 --> 00:48:31,610
on the decision-making
that went into Vietnam.

1016
00:48:31,610 --> 00:48:32,510
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Okay.

1017
00:48:32,510 --> 00:48:35,450
Word is, he doved.
Pretty hard.

1018
00:48:35,450 --> 00:48:37,520
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Would he have access
to the study?

1019
00:48:37,520 --> 00:48:39,620
Pretty sure RAND had a copy.

1020
00:48:39,620 --> 00:48:42,820
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> No shit. All right,
well, can you find him?

1021
00:48:42,830 --> 00:48:44,990
Thought maybe I'd try.

1022
00:48:44,990 --> 00:48:46,060
<font color="#ff00ff">(INTERCOM BUZZES)</font>

1023
00:48:48,300 --> 00:48:50,700
<font color="#138ce9">DEBBIE:</font> <i>I've got
Mrs. Graham on the line.</i>

1024
00:48:51,900 --> 00:48:53,630
Katharine.

1025
00:48:53,640 --> 00:48:57,400
<font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> <i>Hey, listen,
I've got tomorrow's headline.</i>

1026
00:48:57,410 --> 00:49:00,470
Oh, Christ, okay, again?

1027
00:49:00,480 --> 00:49:02,610
<i>John Mitchell contacted</i>
The Times.

1028
00:49:02,610 --> 00:49:05,750
<i>Seems the President is going
to seek an injunction.</i>

1029
00:49:06,310 --> 00:49:08,280
No, shit.

1030
00:49:08,280 --> 00:49:10,550
This means that we're in
the goddamn ballgame.

1031
00:49:10,550 --> 00:49:12,790
Because if <i>The Times</i>
gets shut down...

1032
00:49:12,790 --> 00:49:13,890
<i>If they get shut down,</i>

1033
00:49:13,890 --> 00:49:16,760
<i>there is no ballgame.
Ballgame's over.</i>

1034
00:49:16,760 --> 00:49:17,790
Now, Katharine,

1035
00:49:17,790 --> 00:49:20,430
anybody would kill
to have a crack at this.

1036
00:49:20,430 --> 00:49:23,230
<i>Well, sure, but not if it
means breaking the law.</i>

1037
00:49:23,230 --> 00:49:27,400
<i>If a federal judge stops</i>
The Times <i>from publishing...</i>

1038
00:49:27,400 --> 00:49:29,870
<i>well, I don't see how
we could publish...</i>

1039
00:49:29,870 --> 00:49:32,610
<i>even if we could
get hold of a copy.</i>

1040
00:49:35,340 --> 00:49:38,510
<i>Ben?
You have something?</i>

1041
00:49:39,610 --> 00:49:41,250
No.

1042
00:49:41,250 --> 00:49:44,350
<i>Okay, so then there's
nothing to talk about really.</i>

1043
00:49:44,350 --> 00:49:47,420
No, nothing
to talk about at all...

1044
00:49:47,420 --> 00:49:50,460
but thank you for the tip,
Mrs. Graham.

1045
00:49:50,460 --> 00:49:51,560
<font color="#ff00ff">(BOTH CHUCKLE)</font>

1046
00:49:51,560 --> 00:49:53,800
What are you still doing here?

1047
00:49:57,370 --> 00:49:59,570
<font color="#ff00ff">(TRAFFIC NOISES)</font>

1048
00:50:17,550 --> 00:50:19,060
<font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> Excuse me.

1049
00:50:22,830 --> 00:50:24,090
All right.

1050
00:50:25,530 --> 00:50:26,930
<font color="#ff00ff">(INDISTINCT CHATTER)</font>

1051
00:50:26,930 --> 00:50:28,190
Oh, there she is.

1052
00:50:28,200 --> 00:50:29,800
- <font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> Hello.
- How are ya, Kay?

1053
00:50:29,800 --> 00:50:32,070
Good morning, everyone.
Good to see you.

1054
00:50:32,070 --> 00:50:32,930
<font color="#138ce9">MAN:</font> <i>Hello?</i>

1055
00:50:32,940 --> 00:50:34,630
Yeah, I'm looking
for Dan Ellsberg.

1056
00:50:34,640 --> 00:50:36,400
<i>He doesn't work here anymore.</i>

1057
00:50:36,400 --> 00:50:38,240
Do you know where he is now?

1058
00:50:38,240 --> 00:50:40,370
<i>No, I don't. Who is this?</i>

1059
00:50:40,380 --> 00:50:41,840
Thank you.

1060
00:50:41,840 --> 00:50:44,410
<font color="#138ce9">EXCHANGE PRESIDENT:</font> And it is
my great privilege to welcome

1061
00:50:44,410 --> 00:50:46,510
The Washington Post Company...

1062
00:50:46,520 --> 00:50:49,020
to the American
Stock Exchange.

1063
00:50:53,760 --> 00:50:56,260
More than a privilege,
Mrs. Graham.

1064
00:50:56,260 --> 00:50:57,790
This is a real honor.

1065
00:50:57,790 --> 00:50:58,760
<font color="#ff00ff">(LINE RINGING)</font>

1066
00:50:58,760 --> 00:50:59,860
<font color="#138ce9">KAREN:</font> <i>Hello, this is Karen.</i>

1067
00:50:59,860 --> 00:51:01,290
Yeah, I'm looking
for Dan Ellsberg.

1068
00:51:01,300 --> 00:51:02,900
<i>You got the wrong number.</i>

1069
00:51:05,200 --> 00:51:06,300
Speech.

1070
00:51:06,300 --> 00:51:08,640
Go and project
confidence, Kay.

1071
00:51:10,440 --> 00:51:11,640
Gentlemen...

1072
00:51:12,410 --> 00:51:14,970
thank you all for helping make

1073
00:51:14,980 --> 00:51:17,780
The Washington Post
a more robust company.

1074
00:51:18,480 --> 00:51:19,780
<font color="#ff00ff">(LINE RINGING)</font>

1075
00:51:19,780 --> 00:51:21,550
<font color="#138ce9">RECEPTIONIST:</font> <i>Center
for International Studies.</i>

1076
00:51:21,550 --> 00:51:23,350
Yeah, I'm looking
for Dan Ellsberg.

1077
00:51:23,350 --> 00:51:24,890
<i>He's not here.</i>

1078
00:51:26,050 --> 00:51:27,690
But he still works there?

1079
00:51:27,690 --> 00:51:30,660
<i>Yes. Can I take a message?</i>

1080
00:51:30,660 --> 00:51:33,430
Uh, tell him
Ben Bagdikian called.

1081
00:51:33,430 --> 00:51:34,530
<font color="#138ce9">EXCHANGE PRESIDENT:</font> Congratulations.

1082
00:51:34,530 --> 00:51:35,590
<font color="#138ce9">PHOTOGRAPHER:</font> Guys, why don't we

1083
00:51:35,600 --> 00:51:36,930
get together for a photograph?

1084
00:51:36,930 --> 00:51:38,100
<font color="#138ce9">EXCHANGE PRESIDENT:</font> Yes.
<font color="#138ce9">PAUL:</font> Good idea. Absolutely.

1085
00:51:38,100 --> 00:51:39,400
<font color="#138ce9">PHOTOGRAPHER:</font> Here we go.
<font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> Let me see it.

1086
00:51:39,400 --> 00:51:41,370
- <font color="#138ce9">PAUL:</font> Smile, Kay.
- Shall I hold it?

1087
00:51:41,370 --> 00:51:43,040
You just bought
a share of <i>The Post!</i>

1088
00:51:43,040 --> 00:51:45,570
I know. I'm so happy.

1089
00:51:45,570 --> 00:51:50,880
1.35 million shares
at $24.50 a share.

1090
00:51:50,880 --> 00:51:53,850
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHEERING)</font>

1091
00:51:53,850 --> 00:51:56,280
I believe this will not only
make <i>The Post</i> solvent...

1092
00:51:56,290 --> 00:51:58,550
but stronger
than it ever has been.

1093
00:51:58,550 --> 00:51:59,690
- To <i>The Post!</i>
- <font color="#138ce9">ALL:</font> <i>The Post!</i>

1094
00:51:59,690 --> 00:52:01,460
He said to call
from a secure phone.

1095
00:52:01,460 --> 00:52:02,760
Mmm-hmm.

1096
00:52:09,700 --> 00:52:11,300
I hear
Kennedy said Phil Graham

1097
00:52:11,300 --> 00:52:12,730
was the smartest man
he ever met.

1098
00:52:12,730 --> 00:52:15,540
Yeah, for Kay's father to hand
her husband the company...

1099
00:52:15,540 --> 00:52:17,440
says something about the guy.

1100
00:52:17,440 --> 00:52:20,740
I thought it said something
about the time.

1101
00:52:20,740 --> 00:52:22,240
<font color="#138ce9">HOWARD:</font> Turn it up.

1102
00:52:22,240 --> 00:52:23,880
<font color="#138ce9">WALTER CRONKITE:</font> <i>Good evening.</i>
The New York Times <i>late today</i>

1103
00:52:23,880 --> 00:52:26,050
<i>was barred,
at least until Saturday...</i>

1104
00:52:26,050 --> 00:52:28,780
<i>from publishing any more
classified documents...</i>

1105
00:52:28,780 --> 00:52:32,590
<i>dealing with the cause and
conduct of the Vietnam War.</i>

1106
00:52:32,590 --> 00:52:34,520
The Times, <i>true to its word...</i>

1107
00:52:34,520 --> 00:52:36,060
<i>said it would abide
by the decision</i>

1108
00:52:36,060 --> 00:52:38,020
<i>of Federal Judge
Murray Gurfein...</i>

1109
00:52:38,030 --> 00:52:40,290
<i>but will resist
a permanent injunction</i>

1110
00:52:40,290 --> 00:52:41,660
<i>at a hearing Friday.</i>

1111
00:52:41,660 --> 00:52:43,600
<i>The Nixon administration
have charged that</i>

1112
00:52:43,600 --> 00:52:45,670
<i>the final two parts of</i>
The Times' <i>series...</i>

1113
00:52:45,670 --> 00:52:47,400
<i>would result in
irreparable injury</i>

1114
00:52:47,400 --> 00:52:49,040
<i>to the national defense.</i>

1115
00:52:49,040 --> 00:52:50,800
Hell, why bother
fighting the communists?

1116
00:52:50,810 --> 00:52:52,510
Think Jefferson just
rolled over in his grave.

1117
00:52:52,510 --> 00:52:55,540
Have the courts ever stopped a
paper from publishing before?

1118
00:52:55,540 --> 00:52:59,110
Not in the history
of the republic.

1119
00:52:59,110 --> 00:53:01,480
Good thing
we're not part of this mess.

1120
00:53:01,480 --> 00:53:04,720
I'd give my left one
to be in this mess.

1121
00:53:04,720 --> 00:53:07,120
There's our
front page lede tomorrow.

1122
00:53:07,120 --> 00:53:08,660
Chal, that's yours.

1123
00:53:09,220 --> 00:53:11,120
All right.

1124
00:53:11,130 --> 00:53:14,100
Party's over.
Let's get back to our jobs.

1125
00:53:16,700 --> 00:53:17,900
<font color="#ff00ff">(TV SWITCHES OFF)</font>

1126
00:53:22,270 --> 00:53:24,270
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHATTERING)</font>

1127
00:53:29,210 --> 00:53:32,180
- <font color="#138ce9">MR. BOSTON:</font> <i>Hello?</i>
- Hi, it's Ben.

1128
00:53:32,180 --> 00:53:33,950
- <i>Yes.</i>
- Dan?

1129
00:53:33,950 --> 00:53:35,110
<i>No.</i>

1130
00:53:35,120 --> 00:53:38,990
Oh, I'm trying to get a hold
of a fella I used to know...

1131
00:53:38,990 --> 00:53:41,450
<i>617-597-4580.</i>

1132
00:53:41,460 --> 00:53:42,760
Okay.

1133
00:53:45,560 --> 00:53:47,330
Hold on.

1134
00:53:48,600 --> 00:53:50,300
Was it 4580?

1135
00:53:50,300 --> 00:53:52,130
<i>Call from another phone.</i>

1136
00:53:52,130 --> 00:53:56,240
617-597-4580.

1137
00:54:05,980 --> 00:54:10,290
617-597-4580.

1138
00:54:17,130 --> 00:54:18,660
<font color="#ff00ff">(LINE RINGS)</font>

1139
00:54:18,660 --> 00:54:20,060
<font color="#138ce9">DANIEL:</font> <i>Hello?</i>

1140
00:54:20,060 --> 00:54:23,130
- Yeah, I'm looking for...
- <i>Yeah. Hey, Ben, it's Dan.</i>

1141
00:54:23,130 --> 00:54:26,630
Dan, it's good
to hear your voice.

1142
00:54:26,630 --> 00:54:28,340
<i>Yeah, it's been a while.</i>

1143
00:54:28,340 --> 00:54:29,710
Yeah.

1144
00:54:44,090 --> 00:54:45,090
<font color="#ff00ff">(KNOCKS)</font>

1145
00:54:47,860 --> 00:54:50,060
- <font color="#138ce9">DANIEL:</font> Who is it?
- It's Ben.

1146
00:54:59,500 --> 00:55:00,740
Ben.

1147
00:55:01,070 --> 00:55:02,370
Dan.

1148
00:55:07,810 --> 00:55:10,540
The study had 47 volumes.

1149
00:55:10,550 --> 00:55:12,280
I slipped out
a couple at a time.

1150
00:55:12,280 --> 00:55:13,820
Took me months to copy it all.

1151
00:55:17,590 --> 00:55:18,820
What the hell?

1152
00:55:18,820 --> 00:55:21,790
Well, we were
all former government guys.

1153
00:55:21,790 --> 00:55:23,690
Top clearance, all of that.

1154
00:55:23,690 --> 00:55:25,730
McNamara wanted
academics to have

1155
00:55:25,730 --> 00:55:27,560
the chance to examine
what had happened.

1156
00:55:27,560 --> 00:55:28,660
He would say to us,

1157
00:55:28,660 --> 00:55:30,360
"Let the chips fall
where they may."

1158
00:55:30,360 --> 00:55:31,570
Brave man.

1159
00:55:31,570 --> 00:55:34,330
Well, I think guilt was a
bigger motivator than courage.

1160
00:55:34,340 --> 00:55:36,240
McNamara didn't lie
as well as the rest...

1161
00:55:36,240 --> 00:55:39,340
but I don't think he saw what
was coming, what we'd find.

1162
00:55:39,340 --> 00:55:41,570
But it didn't take him long
to figure out...

1163
00:55:41,580 --> 00:55:42,680
well, for us all
to figure out

1164
00:55:42,680 --> 00:55:44,510
if the public ever saw
these papers...

1165
00:55:44,510 --> 00:55:46,150
they would turn
against the war.

1166
00:55:46,150 --> 00:55:49,150
Covert ops, guaranteed debt,
rigged elections?

1167
00:55:49,150 --> 00:55:53,090
It's all in there.
Ike, Kennedy, Johnson.

1168
00:55:53,090 --> 00:55:54,790
They violated
the Geneva Convention.

1169
00:55:54,790 --> 00:55:57,520
They lied to Congress
and they lied to the public.

1170
00:55:57,530 --> 00:56:01,690
They knew we couldn't win
and still sent boys to die.

1171
00:56:01,700 --> 00:56:03,430
What about Nixon?

1172
00:56:04,700 --> 00:56:06,500
He's just carrying on
like all the others.

1173
00:56:06,500 --> 00:56:09,770
Too afraid to be the one who
loses the war on his watch.

1174
00:56:11,170 --> 00:56:14,040
Someone said this
at some point...

1175
00:56:14,040 --> 00:56:16,980
about why we stayed
when we knew we were losing.

1176
00:56:17,950 --> 00:56:20,480
10% was to help
the South Vietnamese.

1177
00:56:20,480 --> 00:56:22,350
20% was to hold back
the commies.

1178
00:56:23,320 --> 00:56:25,550
70% was to avoid

1179
00:56:25,550 --> 00:56:28,320
the humiliation
of an American defeat.

1180
00:56:28,320 --> 00:56:32,530
70% of those boys...

1181
00:56:32,530 --> 00:56:34,830
just to avoid
being humiliated?

1182
00:56:35,430 --> 00:56:37,070
That stuck with me.

1183
00:56:37,400 --> 00:56:38,530
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1184
00:56:43,670 --> 00:56:45,970
<font color="#ff00ff">(BREATHES HEAVILY)</font>

1185
00:56:45,970 --> 00:56:47,910
They're gonna come after you,
you know.

1186
00:56:47,910 --> 00:56:50,210
And I gotta be honest...

1187
00:56:50,210 --> 00:56:53,110
the bread crumbs
weren't too hard to follow.

1188
00:56:54,620 --> 00:56:55,850
I know.

1189
00:56:57,950 --> 00:57:00,320
They're gonna
lock you up, Dan.

1190
00:57:00,320 --> 00:57:03,460
Wouldn't you go to prison
to stop this war?

1191
00:57:05,330 --> 00:57:07,530
Theoretically, sure.

1192
00:57:10,770 --> 00:57:14,100
You are gonna
publish these documents?

1193
00:57:16,440 --> 00:57:17,840
Yeah.

1194
00:57:18,640 --> 00:57:21,380
Even with the injunction?

1195
00:57:23,010 --> 00:57:24,180
Yes.

1196
00:57:26,780 --> 00:57:28,080
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font>

1197
00:57:28,080 --> 00:57:31,320
Well, then it's not
so theoretical then, is it?

1198
00:57:35,620 --> 00:57:37,230
<font color="#ff00ff">(LIGHTER CLINKING)</font>

1199
00:57:41,930 --> 00:57:45,070
I'm gonna go do some
work in the studio.

1200
00:57:53,240 --> 00:57:56,180
My day was great,
thanks for asking.

1201
00:58:12,530 --> 00:58:15,360
That picture makes me sad.

1202
00:58:16,560 --> 00:58:18,230
Me too.

1203
00:58:18,230 --> 00:58:19,570
<font color="#ff00ff">(PHONE RINGS)</font>

1204
00:58:23,310 --> 00:58:25,000
- Bradlee.
- <font color="#138ce9">BAGDIKIAN:</font> <i>I'm in Boston.</i>

1205
00:58:25,010 --> 00:58:27,240
I'm gonna need two seats.

1206
00:58:27,240 --> 00:58:28,170
Why?

1207
00:58:28,180 --> 00:58:30,340
I'm gonna need to
buy two seats

1208
00:58:30,350 --> 00:58:31,880
on the first flight
out tomorrow...

1209
00:58:31,880 --> 00:58:33,480
probably first class.

1210
00:58:34,580 --> 00:58:36,380
No shit, you have them?

1211
00:58:38,820 --> 00:58:41,290
Well then just get
your ass back here...

1212
00:58:41,290 --> 00:58:42,860
and come
straight to the house.

1213
00:58:42,860 --> 00:58:44,360
Get Chal and Meg
and the others.

1214
00:58:44,360 --> 00:58:45,630
I don't want
the whole newsroom

1215
00:58:45,630 --> 00:58:46,830
knowing about this yet.

1216
00:58:46,830 --> 00:58:48,130
I gotta go.

1217
00:58:48,130 --> 00:58:50,600
Didn't you just invite
a bunch of people over?

1218
00:58:50,600 --> 00:58:51,800
Yeah.

1219
00:58:51,800 --> 00:58:54,030
Yeah, they'll show up
sometime tomorrow.

1220
00:58:54,040 --> 00:58:55,170
When sometime tomorrow?

1221
00:58:55,170 --> 00:58:56,900
Is this a breakfast thing
or a lunch thing?

1222
00:58:56,900 --> 00:58:59,040
- Don't know.
- Do you need me to get things?

1223
00:58:59,040 --> 00:59:00,770
- Nah, we'll figure it all out.
- Okay.

1224
00:59:00,780 --> 00:59:02,810
- Well, where are you going?
- <font color="#ff00ff">(GRUNTS)</font> Out.

1225
00:59:02,810 --> 00:59:04,480
- You going to the newsroom?
- No.

1226
00:59:04,480 --> 00:59:05,980
Love you, bear.

1227
00:59:05,980 --> 00:59:07,180
<font color="#ff00ff">(DOORBELL RINGS)</font>

1228
00:59:07,180 --> 00:59:09,320
I got a cake.
I hope it's okay?

1229
00:59:09,320 --> 00:59:12,250
Oh, sure, as long as nobody
counts the candles.

1230
00:59:14,090 --> 00:59:16,760
Uh, sorry to barge in again.

1231
00:59:16,760 --> 00:59:18,990
Maybe I should give you a key.

1232
00:59:18,990 --> 00:59:21,760
Ah, not here
to crash your party.

1233
00:59:21,760 --> 00:59:22,900
What's up?

1234
00:59:22,900 --> 00:59:25,000
Well, I could use a minute.

1235
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:27,300
- <font color="#ff00ff">(MUSIC PLAYING)</font>
- <font color="#ff00ff">(PEOPLE CHATTERING)</font>

1236
00:59:32,110 --> 00:59:34,140
So, can I ask you a
hypothetical question?

1237
00:59:34,140 --> 00:59:36,410
Oh, dear, I don't like
hypothetical questions.

1238
00:59:36,410 --> 00:59:37,880
Well, I don't think
you're gonna

1239
00:59:37,880 --> 00:59:39,410
like the real one either.

1240
00:59:42,550 --> 00:59:43,990
Do you have the papers?

1241
00:59:45,620 --> 00:59:46,990
Not yet.

1242
00:59:49,290 --> 00:59:50,420
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1243
00:59:50,420 --> 00:59:54,060
<font color="#ff00ff">(STUTTERS)</font> Oh, gosh,
because you know...

1244
00:59:54,060 --> 00:59:56,960
the position
that would put me in.

1245
00:59:56,960 --> 00:59:58,430
You know, we have language

1246
00:59:58,430 --> 01:00:00,100
in the prospectus
that we've...

1247
01:00:00,100 --> 01:00:02,570
Yeah, I know that the
bankers can change their mind.

1248
01:00:02,570 --> 01:00:04,770
And I know what is at stake.

1249
01:00:04,770 --> 01:00:06,070
You know...

1250
01:00:06,070 --> 01:00:08,670
the only couple I knew
that both Kennedy

1251
01:00:08,680 --> 01:00:10,280
and LBJ wanted
to socialize with...

1252
01:00:10,280 --> 01:00:14,520
was you and your husband and
you owned the damn paper.

1253
01:00:16,190 --> 01:00:18,080
Of course that's the way
things worked.

1254
01:00:18,090 --> 01:00:20,350
Politicians and the press,
they trusted each other...

1255
01:00:20,360 --> 01:00:22,050
so they could go to
the same dinner party

1256
01:00:22,060 --> 01:00:23,560
and drink cocktails
and tell jokes...

1257
01:00:23,560 --> 01:00:25,590
while there was a war
waging in Vietnam.

1258
01:00:25,590 --> 01:00:27,290
Ben, I don't know
what we're talking about.

1259
01:00:27,290 --> 01:00:29,300
I'm not protecting Lyndon.

1260
01:00:29,300 --> 01:00:30,660
No, you got his former
Secretary of Defense,

1261
01:00:30,670 --> 01:00:31,800
Robert McNamara...

1262
01:00:31,800 --> 01:00:33,970
the man
who commissioned this study.

1263
01:00:33,970 --> 01:00:35,370
He's one of about
a dozen party guests...

1264
01:00:35,370 --> 01:00:37,170
- out on your patio.
- I'm not protecting him.

1265
01:00:37,170 --> 01:00:38,240
I'm not protecting
any of them.

1266
01:00:38,240 --> 01:00:39,540
I'm protecting the paper.

1267
01:00:39,540 --> 01:00:43,240
Yeah? Well, I wasn't a stooge
for Jack Kennedy.

1268
01:00:43,240 --> 01:00:44,880
The night he was assassinated

1269
01:00:44,880 --> 01:00:47,210
Tony and I were down
at the Naval Hospital...

1270
01:00:47,220 --> 01:00:50,950
so we would be there to meet
Jackie when she landed.

1271
01:00:50,950 --> 01:00:52,020
She was bringing Jack's body

1272
01:00:52,020 --> 01:00:53,820
back on the plane
from Dallas...

1273
01:00:53,820 --> 01:00:56,190
and she walked into the room.

1274
01:00:56,190 --> 01:00:58,120
She was still
wearing that pink suit

1275
01:00:58,130 --> 01:01:00,660
with Jack's blood all over it.

1276
01:01:00,660 --> 01:01:03,860
She fell into Tony's arms
and they held each other...

1277
01:01:03,860 --> 01:01:06,070
for quite a long time.

1278
01:01:07,840 --> 01:01:10,370
And then Jackie looked at me
and said...

1279
01:01:10,370 --> 01:01:13,040
"None of this,
none of what you see,

1280
01:01:13,040 --> 01:01:14,310
"none of what I say...

1281
01:01:14,310 --> 01:01:18,880
"is ever going to be
in your newspaper, Ben."

1282
01:01:18,880 --> 01:01:21,850
And that just about
broke my heart.

1283
01:01:21,850 --> 01:01:24,020
I never... <font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font>

1284
01:01:24,020 --> 01:01:25,790
I never thought of Jack
as a source,

1285
01:01:25,790 --> 01:01:27,820
I thought of him as a friend.

1286
01:01:27,820 --> 01:01:30,190
And that was my mistake.

1287
01:01:30,190 --> 01:01:33,660
And it was something that
Jack knew all along.

1288
01:01:33,660 --> 01:01:36,630
We can't be both.
We have to choose.

1289
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:38,600
And...

1290
01:01:38,600 --> 01:01:40,270
And that's the point.

1291
01:01:40,270 --> 01:01:42,300
The days of us all
smoking cigars together

1292
01:01:42,300 --> 01:01:45,040
down on Pennsylvania Avenue
are over.

1293
01:01:45,040 --> 01:01:49,240
Your friend McNamara's
study proves that.

1294
01:01:50,040 --> 01:01:52,210
The way they lied.

1295
01:01:53,580 --> 01:01:55,750
The way they lied.

1296
01:01:55,750 --> 01:01:57,850
Those days have to be over.

1297
01:01:59,490 --> 01:02:02,590
We have to be the check
on their power.

1298
01:02:02,590 --> 01:02:04,860
If we don't
hold them accountable,

1299
01:02:04,860 --> 01:02:07,300
I mean, my God, who will?

1300
01:02:08,630 --> 01:02:10,400
Well, I've never
smoked a cigar...

1301
01:02:10,400 --> 01:02:13,100
and I have no problem
holding Lyndon or Jack...

1302
01:02:13,100 --> 01:02:15,470
or Bob or any of them
accountable.

1303
01:02:15,470 --> 01:02:17,770
But we can't
hold them accountable

1304
01:02:17,770 --> 01:02:19,670
if we don't have a newspaper.

1305
01:02:21,440 --> 01:02:24,010
When I get my hands
on that study...

1306
01:02:24,010 --> 01:02:26,650
what are you going to do,
Mrs. Graham?

1307
01:02:30,020 --> 01:02:32,050
Oh, uh...

1308
01:02:32,050 --> 01:02:33,620
Happy birthday, by the way.

1309
01:02:33,620 --> 01:02:36,160
- <font color="#ff00ff">(MUSIC PLAYING)</font>
- <font color="#ff00ff">(CHATTERING)</font>

1310
01:02:36,160 --> 01:02:38,520
Oh, that's not what I heard.

1311
01:02:38,530 --> 01:02:39,730
Am I right?

1312
01:02:39,730 --> 01:02:41,500
<font color="#ff00ff">(LAUGHING)</font>

1313
01:02:45,370 --> 01:02:46,870
- Hi. Good morning.
- Club soda.

1314
01:02:46,870 --> 01:02:48,540
- Enjoy your flight.
- Yes, thank you.

1315
01:02:49,370 --> 01:02:51,470
Sir, I'm gonna need
to put your seat

1316
01:02:51,470 --> 01:02:53,610
in the full upright position
before takeoff.

1317
01:02:53,610 --> 01:02:54,640
<font color="#ff00ff">(GRUNTS)</font> Yeah.

1318
01:02:55,240 --> 01:02:57,410
Must be precious cargo.

1319
01:02:57,410 --> 01:03:00,580
Yeah. It's just
government secrets.

1320
01:03:00,580 --> 01:03:04,320
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font> Please fasten
your seatbelt. Thank you.

1321
01:03:17,330 --> 01:03:20,400
- You know why we're here?
- Beats me.

1322
01:03:20,400 --> 01:03:22,170
- Hi, Marina.
- Hi.

1323
01:03:22,170 --> 01:03:24,400
- Do you want lemonade?
- Little early for me.

1324
01:03:24,410 --> 01:03:26,070
Loosen up, I'm buying.

1325
01:03:26,070 --> 01:03:28,370
What kinda lemonade
do you have there?

1326
01:03:28,380 --> 01:03:31,240
Uh... It's the one
with the lemons in it.

1327
01:03:31,250 --> 01:03:32,450
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font> Okay.

1328
01:03:33,710 --> 01:03:35,250
<font color="#138ce9">BAGDIKIAN:</font> There you go.

1329
01:03:37,320 --> 01:03:39,520
Phil, help me out.

1330
01:03:41,220 --> 01:03:43,360
Grab my briefcase.

1331
01:03:45,130 --> 01:03:46,630
- Is that...?
- Yep.

1332
01:03:46,630 --> 01:03:48,430
- <font color="#ff00ff">(CAR DOOR SHUTS)</font>
- <font color="#ff00ff">(CAR DRIVES AWAY)</font>

1333
01:03:59,370 --> 01:04:00,910
It's not the full report

1334
01:04:00,910 --> 01:04:03,350
but it's over
4,000 pages of it.

1335
01:04:06,210 --> 01:04:08,350
-<font color="#138ce9"> MEG:</font> Are these in order?
- I don't think so.

1336
01:04:08,350 --> 01:04:09,650
There are no page numbers.

1337
01:04:09,650 --> 01:04:11,550
Yeah, that's where the
top secret stamps were.

1338
01:04:11,550 --> 01:04:13,050
My source had to cut 'em off.

1339
01:04:13,050 --> 01:04:14,490
I was supposed to
retire on Friday.

1340
01:04:14,490 --> 01:04:16,020
Ben, how we supposed
to comb through

1341
01:04:16,020 --> 01:04:17,160
4,000 pages of material?

1342
01:04:17,160 --> 01:04:18,320
They're not even
loosely organized?

1343
01:04:18,330 --> 01:04:19,590
<i>The Times</i> had three months.

1344
01:04:19,590 --> 01:04:20,790
There's no way
we can possibly get this done.

1345
01:04:20,790 --> 01:04:22,560
He's right. We've got
less than eight hours.

1346
01:04:22,560 --> 01:04:24,200
We could shoot for city.
Then we'd have ten.

1347
01:04:24,200 --> 01:04:25,670
Hey, hey, hey.
For the last six years

1348
01:04:25,670 --> 01:04:27,170
we've been playin' catch-up...

1349
01:04:27,170 --> 01:04:28,270
and now thanks to

1350
01:04:28,270 --> 01:04:29,670
the President
of the United States...

1351
01:04:29,670 --> 01:04:31,300
who, by the way,
is taking a shit

1352
01:04:31,310 --> 01:04:32,970
all over
the First Amendment...

1353
01:04:32,970 --> 01:04:34,640
we have the goods.

1354
01:04:34,640 --> 01:04:36,740
And we don't have
any competition.

1355
01:04:36,740 --> 01:04:38,780
There's dozens
of stories in here.

1356
01:04:38,780 --> 01:04:41,750
<i>The Times</i> has barely
scratched the surface.

1357
01:04:41,750 --> 01:04:44,920
We have ten hours
'til the deadline...

1358
01:04:45,320 --> 01:04:47,360
so we dig in.

1359
01:04:50,760 --> 01:04:53,030
<font color="#138ce9">MEG:</font> I think this memo's
from McNamara.

1360
01:04:53,030 --> 01:04:54,590
"It is my belief
that there should be

1361
01:04:54,600 --> 01:04:56,430
"a three- or four-week pause
in bombing."

1362
01:04:56,430 --> 01:04:58,570
Wait, wait, wait. I saw
the other half of that memo.

1363
01:04:58,570 --> 01:05:01,930
Anyone have the back half of
a cable from Dulles in '54?

1364
01:05:01,940 --> 01:05:03,840
I thought I saw one from July.

1365
01:05:03,840 --> 01:05:06,140
Yeah, here it is. "The reasons
for this belief...

1366
01:05:06,140 --> 01:05:08,040
"are that we must
lay a foundation

1367
01:05:08,040 --> 01:05:09,480
"in the mind
of the American public."

1368
01:05:09,480 --> 01:05:11,450
That's it! That's it!

1369
01:05:12,780 --> 01:05:14,410
So Johnson wasn't trying
to make peace.

1370
01:05:14,420 --> 01:05:15,710
He was just
manipulating the public?

1371
01:05:15,720 --> 01:05:18,720
Eyes out for a suspension
in bombing from when?

1372
01:05:18,720 --> 01:05:20,320
'65 to '68.

1373
01:05:20,320 --> 01:05:21,650
<font color="#138ce9">CHALMERS:</font> What about a memo

1374
01:05:21,660 --> 01:05:25,020
from Eisenhower's special
committee on Indochina?

1375
01:05:25,030 --> 01:05:26,130
Uh, Meg read
a part of one to me.

1376
01:05:26,130 --> 01:05:27,190
Meg?

1377
01:05:27,190 --> 01:05:28,430
<font color="#138ce9">BAGDIKIAN:</font> Anybody see a mention

1378
01:05:28,430 --> 01:05:29,660
of the RAND Viet Cong study?

1379
01:05:29,660 --> 01:05:32,000
Yeah, I think this might be
from your RAND study.

1380
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:33,570
"VC are deeply committed.

1381
01:05:33,570 --> 01:05:35,600
"South Vietnam
is a lost cause."

1382
01:05:35,600 --> 01:05:37,600
- Whoa! There you go.
- Bingo.

1383
01:05:37,610 --> 01:05:39,110
- All right.
- <font color="#138ce9">CHALMERS:</font> Meg, I need the...

1384
01:05:39,110 --> 01:05:40,240
<font color="#138ce9">MEG:</font> Yeah,
I put it on the shelf.

1385
01:05:40,240 --> 01:05:42,910
Couple of piles.
We're getting somewhere.

1386
01:05:42,910 --> 01:05:45,710
All right, it's 1:{\c}30.
Four o'clock story conference.

1387
01:05:45,710 --> 01:05:47,850
Can I interest anyone
in some lemonade?

1388
01:05:47,850 --> 01:05:49,550
- <font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Yes!
- Does it have vodka in it?

1389
01:05:49,550 --> 01:05:51,050
I don't put vodka
in my lemonade.

1390
01:05:51,050 --> 01:05:52,150
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Go easy on the kid.

1391
01:05:52,150 --> 01:05:53,490
<font color="#138ce9">CHALMERS:</font> Why not?

1392
01:05:53,490 --> 01:05:54,820
- <font color="#138ce9">MURREY:</font> How much, sweetheart?
- <font color="#138ce9">MARINA:</font> A quarter.

1393
01:05:54,820 --> 01:05:55,890
It's 50 cents.

1394
01:05:55,890 --> 01:05:57,990
- Inflation.
- <font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Price is going up.

1395
01:06:01,360 --> 01:06:02,960
Mr. Bradlee.

1396
01:06:02,960 --> 01:06:04,260
Roger Clark.

1397
01:06:04,270 --> 01:06:06,360
Oh, you're Roger Clark?

1398
01:06:06,370 --> 01:06:08,270
It's nice to
meet you in person.

1399
01:06:08,270 --> 01:06:11,870
You are our
senior legal counsel.

1400
01:06:11,870 --> 01:06:13,840
Yes, we've spoken
on the phone.

1401
01:06:13,840 --> 01:06:15,540
My voice should
sound familiar.

1402
01:06:15,540 --> 01:06:18,380
When did you
finish law school?

1403
01:06:18,380 --> 01:06:20,780
- I graduated...
- Rhetorical question.

1404
01:06:20,780 --> 01:06:22,920
You know,
the guy we had before you

1405
01:06:22,920 --> 01:06:24,880
is now Secretary of State.

1406
01:06:24,890 --> 01:06:27,690
I did not know that.

1407
01:06:27,690 --> 01:06:29,620
A little joke,
perhaps not the time.

1408
01:06:29,620 --> 01:06:31,220
What exactly
can I help you with...

1409
01:06:31,230 --> 01:06:34,060
So, why would the CIA Director
send a memo on war policy?

1410
01:06:34,060 --> 01:06:35,930
<font color="#138ce9">PHIL:</font> Because they weren't
calling it a war yet.

1411
01:06:35,930 --> 01:06:37,960
Okay, I've got
turkey with mustard.

1412
01:06:37,970 --> 01:06:39,230
Roast beef with horseradish.

1413
01:06:39,230 --> 01:06:41,770
- Howard, come look at this.
- Chal, you've gotta see this.

1414
01:06:41,770 --> 01:06:44,070
It's a full analysis
of McNamara's

1415
01:06:44,070 --> 01:06:45,140
changing view of the war.

1416
01:06:45,140 --> 01:06:46,540
<font color="#138ce9">CHALMERS:</font> Does it say anything
about why he does?

1417
01:06:46,540 --> 01:06:48,270
So we knew they were
gonna assassinate Diem.

1418
01:06:48,280 --> 01:06:49,770
Yeah, and we did
nothing to stop it.

1419
01:06:49,780 --> 01:06:51,610
<font color="#138ce9">MEG:</font> I think I got something
on McNamara on the fireplace.

1420
01:06:51,610 --> 01:06:53,380
The other fireplace.

1421
01:06:53,380 --> 01:06:54,750
<font color="#ff00ff">(OVERLAPPING CHATTER)</font>

1422
01:06:54,750 --> 01:06:56,520
<font color="#138ce9">CHALMERS:</font> Murrey, where's
the back half of this one?

1423
01:06:56,520 --> 01:06:58,090
What's the thing
you just gave me?

1424
01:06:59,420 --> 01:07:01,090
Tell me these aren't
the classified documents

1425
01:07:01,090 --> 01:07:02,520
from the McNamara study.

1426
01:07:02,520 --> 01:07:04,320
4,000 pages of 'em.

1427
01:07:04,330 --> 01:07:07,190
- Hungry?
- I need to use a phone.

1428
01:07:07,190 --> 01:07:09,290
There's one in the other room.

1429
01:07:09,300 --> 01:07:10,530
- <font color="#138ce9">PHIL:</font> Two.
- <font color="#138ce9">MEG:</font> Is that it?

1430
01:07:10,530 --> 01:07:11,960
<font color="#138ce9">PHIL:</font> This is it. This is it.

1431
01:07:11,970 --> 01:07:13,430
<font color="#138ce9">MURREY:</font> Hmm?

1432
01:07:13,430 --> 01:07:15,270
<font color="#138ce9">PHIL:</font> This is
the other half of it.

1433
01:07:15,270 --> 01:07:17,000
<font color="#ff00ff">(SNORING)</font>

1434
01:07:23,380 --> 01:07:25,050
<font color="#ff00ff">(BREATHES DEEPLY)</font>

1435
01:07:26,480 --> 01:07:28,650
Oh, my God.

1436
01:07:30,220 --> 01:07:31,620
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1437
01:07:45,830 --> 01:07:47,800
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1438
01:07:56,280 --> 01:07:59,580
Hi. Thanks for
letting me drop by.

1439
01:07:59,580 --> 01:08:01,910
- Marg still napping?
- Yeah.

1440
01:08:01,920 --> 01:08:03,580
Do you mind
if we talk in the sunroom?

1441
01:08:03,580 --> 01:08:05,020
Just so I can hear her
if she wakes.

1442
01:08:05,020 --> 01:08:06,950
No, of course not.
I can't stay long.

1443
01:08:06,960 --> 01:08:08,650
I've got a big event
at the house later.

1444
01:08:08,660 --> 01:08:11,630
I guess you've read
everything now.

1445
01:08:12,360 --> 01:08:14,330
Yes, I have. I have, yes.

1446
01:08:14,330 --> 01:08:16,500
And I went over it
again this morning.

1447
01:08:16,900 --> 01:08:18,500
All of it.

1448
01:08:19,470 --> 01:08:21,070
And I just...

1449
01:08:22,640 --> 01:08:26,970
Forgive me, Bob, I know you're
dealing with so much...

1450
01:08:28,640 --> 01:08:32,680
but it's just so hard to try
to make sense of why.

1451
01:08:32,680 --> 01:08:35,310
Of how you could have done
all these things.

1452
01:08:35,320 --> 01:08:37,250
How you could
just lie to us all.

1453
01:08:37,250 --> 01:08:41,850
Well, it's easy for the papers
to characterize us as liars.

1454
01:08:41,860 --> 01:08:44,090
We were just trying to
push back...

1455
01:08:44,090 --> 01:08:46,330
No, but you let it
go on and on and on.

1456
01:08:46,330 --> 01:08:49,230
My son is home now and safe,
thank God.

1457
01:08:49,230 --> 01:08:50,960
But you watched him go.

1458
01:08:50,970 --> 01:08:52,330
You knew
we couldn't win over there...

1459
01:08:52,330 --> 01:08:55,700
for years and years and years,
and yet you let me...

1460
01:08:56,940 --> 01:09:00,070
you let so many of our friends
send our boys off.

1461
01:09:00,070 --> 01:09:02,940
Kay, we were doing
the best we could.

1462
01:09:02,940 --> 01:09:06,240
It was domino theory,
containment...

1463
01:09:06,250 --> 01:09:07,780
and eventually we felt

1464
01:09:07,780 --> 01:09:09,710
that military pressure
was the only thing...

1465
01:09:09,720 --> 01:09:11,680
that was gonna drive
Ho Chi Minh to the table.

1466
01:09:11,690 --> 01:09:13,450
Our decision-making
process was...

1467
01:09:13,450 --> 01:09:15,090
Flawed.

1468
01:09:19,830 --> 01:09:23,130
It was flawed.
That's what your study said.

1469
01:09:24,930 --> 01:09:26,170
Yes.

1470
01:09:28,240 --> 01:09:33,270
I do believe that you were
trying to do your best...

1471
01:09:34,240 --> 01:09:36,780
and I know
how difficult it can be

1472
01:09:36,780 --> 01:09:39,040
to make choices that will...

1473
01:09:39,050 --> 01:09:41,680
That's kind of you.

1474
01:09:41,680 --> 01:09:45,320
Well, what comes next
might not be so kind.

1475
01:09:47,390 --> 01:09:49,450
You have the papers.

1476
01:09:49,460 --> 01:09:50,790
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY)</font>

1477
01:09:51,330 --> 01:09:52,790
Let's just say...

1478
01:09:52,790 --> 01:09:56,330
I may have
a big decision to make.

1479
01:09:57,970 --> 01:09:59,830
<font color="#ff00ff">(KAY SIGHS)</font>

1480
01:10:01,540 --> 01:10:03,200
<font color="#138ce9">ANTHONY:</font> They will
argue it's a violation

1481
01:10:03,200 --> 01:10:04,300
of the Espionage Act.

1482
01:10:04,300 --> 01:10:05,540
That is a felony, Ben.

1483
01:10:05,540 --> 01:10:07,470
That's only
if the documents we print

1484
01:10:07,470 --> 01:10:08,810
could damage
the United States.

1485
01:10:08,810 --> 01:10:10,640
There's a federal judge
in New York

1486
01:10:10,640 --> 01:10:11,810
who seems to think
that they could.

1487
01:10:11,810 --> 01:10:13,110
Well, I've got
six seasoned journalists

1488
01:10:13,110 --> 01:10:14,410
in the next room...

1489
01:10:14,420 --> 01:10:16,050
who've been reporting on this
war for the last ten years...

1490
01:10:16,050 --> 01:10:18,180
and I'll lay odds that they
have a better idea...

1491
01:10:18,190 --> 01:10:19,690
of what could damage
the United States

1492
01:10:19,690 --> 01:10:20,820
than some judge...

1493
01:10:20,820 --> 01:10:22,090
who is just now wading

1494
01:10:22,090 --> 01:10:23,820
into this territory
for the first time.

1495
01:10:23,820 --> 01:10:26,260
"Wading." Is that a metaphor
for Vietnam?

1496
01:10:26,260 --> 01:10:29,230
Okay. Ben, look, we know
your reporters are talented.

1497
01:10:29,230 --> 01:10:31,530
But <i>The New York Times</i>
spent three months

1498
01:10:31,530 --> 01:10:33,570
going over these documents.

1499
01:10:33,570 --> 01:10:35,400
You've got, what,
seven hours now

1500
01:10:35,400 --> 01:10:36,740
until the paper goes to press?

1501
01:10:36,740 --> 01:10:39,140
Can you honestly tell me
that that is enough time...

1502
01:10:39,140 --> 01:10:43,210
to make sure
not a single military plan,

1503
01:10:43,210 --> 01:10:44,340
not a single U.S. soldier...

1504
01:10:44,340 --> 01:10:47,250
not a single American life
will be put in harm's way?

1505
01:10:47,250 --> 01:10:48,850
That this will do no damage

1506
01:10:48,850 --> 01:10:51,080
to the United States
if you publish?

1507
01:10:51,090 --> 01:10:52,120
Yes.

1508
01:10:54,320 --> 01:10:55,860
<font color="#138ce9">ROGER:</font> You're sure about that?

1509
01:10:55,860 --> 01:10:56,820
No!

1510
01:10:56,820 --> 01:11:00,060
That's why
I've called you guys.

1511
01:11:00,060 --> 01:11:02,590
<font color="#138ce9">ROBERT:</font> <i>Look, Kay, I know
why</i> The Times <i>ran the story</i>

1512
01:11:02,600 --> 01:11:04,200
<i>but you need to understand...</i>

1513
01:11:04,200 --> 01:11:05,660
the study was for posterity.

1514
01:11:05,670 --> 01:11:07,830
It was written for academics
in the future...

1515
01:11:07,840 --> 01:11:09,630
and right now we're still
in the middle of the war.

1516
01:11:09,640 --> 01:11:11,200
The papers can't be objective.

1517
01:11:11,210 --> 01:11:13,640
And I suppose the public
has a right to know...

1518
01:11:13,640 --> 01:11:15,910
but I would prefer
that the study

1519
01:11:15,910 --> 01:11:17,340
not be made
widely available...

1520
01:11:17,340 --> 01:11:20,410
until it can be read with some
perspective. You understand.

1521
01:11:20,420 --> 01:11:22,050
Mmm.

1522
01:11:22,050 --> 01:11:23,420
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1523
01:11:23,420 --> 01:11:24,880
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font>

1524
01:11:24,890 --> 01:11:27,320
We've been through a lot,
haven't we?

1525
01:11:27,320 --> 01:11:30,760
You and Marg
were there for me...

1526
01:11:30,760 --> 01:11:32,960
at the lowest point
of my life.

1527
01:11:32,960 --> 01:11:36,560
You helped me, you selected
my entire board...

1528
01:11:36,560 --> 01:11:39,230
you're my most
trusted advisor...

1529
01:11:39,230 --> 01:11:40,830
my dear friend.

1530
01:11:41,770 --> 01:11:45,240
But my feelings about that
and about you...

1531
01:11:45,240 --> 01:11:48,940
can't be part of this decision
to publish or not.

1532
01:11:48,940 --> 01:11:53,510
I'm here
asking your advice, Bob...

1533
01:11:53,510 --> 01:11:56,250
not your permission.

1534
01:11:56,250 --> 01:11:59,220
Well, then as one of your
most trusted advisors...

1535
01:11:59,220 --> 01:12:01,520
and someone who knows how much
you care about this company...

1536
01:12:01,520 --> 01:12:02,650
I'm worried, Kay.

1537
01:12:02,660 --> 01:12:04,190
I worked in Washington
for ten years,

1538
01:12:04,190 --> 01:12:05,660
I've seen
these people up close.

1539
01:12:05,660 --> 01:12:07,960
Bobby and Lyndon,
they were tough customers,

1540
01:12:07,960 --> 01:12:10,060
but Nixon is different.

1541
01:12:10,060 --> 01:12:12,300
He's got some real bad
people around him.

1542
01:12:12,300 --> 01:12:14,530
And if you publish he'll
get the very worst of them.

1543
01:12:14,540 --> 01:12:15,770
The Colsons
and the Ehrlichmans

1544
01:12:15,770 --> 01:12:16,900
and he'll crush you.

1545
01:12:16,900 --> 01:12:18,270
I know he's just awful,
but I...

1546
01:12:18,270 --> 01:12:21,140
Nixon's a son of a bitch!
He hates you.

1547
01:12:21,140 --> 01:12:22,140
He hates Ben.

1548
01:12:22,140 --> 01:12:23,310
He's wanted to ruin
the paper for years...

1549
01:12:23,310 --> 01:12:26,110
and you will not get
a second chance, Kay.

1550
01:12:26,110 --> 01:12:28,010
The Richard Nixon I know
will muster

1551
01:12:28,010 --> 01:12:29,680
the full power
of the presidency...

1552
01:12:29,680 --> 01:12:31,680
and if there's a way
to destroy your paper,

1553
01:12:31,690 --> 01:12:33,990
by God, he'll find it.

1554
01:12:36,460 --> 01:12:38,820
<font color="#138ce9">ANTHONY:</font> Publish information
that harms national security.

1555
01:12:38,830 --> 01:12:40,060
I told you,
there is nothing in there.

1556
01:12:40,060 --> 01:12:41,960
If there is, the paper
will be prosecuted.

1557
01:12:41,960 --> 01:12:43,590
Isn't that why you're here?

1558
01:12:43,600 --> 01:12:45,030
Yes, Ben, but if we lose...

1559
01:12:45,030 --> 01:12:46,770
With what we pay you,
you really shouldn't lose.

1560
01:12:46,770 --> 01:12:47,830
Ben, you need
to listen to them.

1561
01:12:47,840 --> 01:12:48,970
Hey, Fritz.
Good to see you.

1562
01:12:48,970 --> 01:12:50,030
This is about
the future of the company

1563
01:12:50,040 --> 01:12:51,340
and ensuring there is one.

1564
01:12:51,340 --> 01:12:53,570
That's a little melodramatic,
don't you think?

1565
01:12:53,570 --> 01:12:54,970
Melodramatic?
You're talking about

1566
01:12:54,970 --> 01:12:58,080
exposing years
of government secrets.

1567
01:12:58,080 --> 01:13:00,710
I can't imagine they're
gonna take that lightly.

1568
01:13:00,710 --> 01:13:02,250
You could jeopardize
the public offering.

1569
01:13:02,250 --> 01:13:04,380
You could jeopardize
our television stations.

1570
01:13:04,390 --> 01:13:06,520
You know a felon can't
hold a broadcast license.

1571
01:13:06,520 --> 01:13:08,550
You think I give two shits
about the television stations?

1572
01:13:08,560 --> 01:13:09,620
You should.
They make a hell of

1573
01:13:09,620 --> 01:13:10,890
a lot more money
than you do...

1574
01:13:10,890 --> 01:13:13,190
and without that revenue
we'll be forced to sell.

1575
01:13:13,190 --> 01:13:15,260
If the government wins
and we're convicted...

1576
01:13:15,260 --> 01:13:18,130
<i>The Washington Post</i> as we
know it will cease to exist.

1577
01:13:18,130 --> 01:13:19,830
If we live in a world
where the government

1578
01:13:19,830 --> 01:13:21,600
can tell us what we can
and cannot print...

1579
01:13:21,600 --> 01:13:22,800
then <i>The Washington Post</i>
as we know it

1580
01:13:22,800 --> 01:13:25,110
has already ceased to exist.

1581
01:13:26,310 --> 01:13:28,010
What if we wait?

1582
01:13:28,880 --> 01:13:30,980
What if we hold off
on printing today

1583
01:13:30,980 --> 01:13:33,380
and instead we call
the Attorney General...

1584
01:13:33,380 --> 01:13:36,150
and we tell him that
we intend to print on Sunday?

1585
01:13:36,150 --> 01:13:37,850
That way we give
them and us time

1586
01:13:37,850 --> 01:13:40,090
to figure out
the legality of all of it...

1587
01:13:40,090 --> 01:13:42,590
while the court in New York
decides <i>The Times'</i> case.

1588
01:13:42,590 --> 01:13:45,060
You're suggesting we alert
the Attorney General...

1589
01:13:45,060 --> 01:13:47,330
to the fact that we
have these documents...

1590
01:13:47,330 --> 01:13:50,230
that we're going to print
in a few days?

1591
01:13:53,800 --> 01:13:57,000
<font color="#ff00ff">(STUTTERS)</font>
Well, yes, that is the idea.

1592
01:13:57,000 --> 01:13:58,600
<font color="#138ce9">BAGDIKIAN:</font> Yeah, well...

1593
01:13:58,610 --> 01:14:00,070
outside of
landing the Hindenburg

1594
01:14:00,070 --> 01:14:01,440
in a lightning storm...

1595
01:14:01,440 --> 01:14:03,740
that's about the shittiest
idea I've ever heard.

1596
01:14:03,740 --> 01:14:05,110
Oh, boy.

1597
01:14:07,950 --> 01:14:10,080
<font color="#ff00ff">(MUSIC PLAYING INSIDE)</font>

1598
01:14:12,720 --> 01:14:14,720
<font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> Oh, here's
the man of the hour.

1599
01:14:14,720 --> 01:14:16,450
<font color="#138ce9">HARRY:</font> Kay.

1600
01:14:16,460 --> 01:14:17,690
<font color="#138ce9">KAY:</font> For you.

1601
01:14:17,690 --> 01:14:18,790
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font> I'm found.

1602
01:14:18,790 --> 01:14:20,090
Thank you, Kay.

1603
01:14:20,090 --> 01:14:21,260
You didn't have to
go through all this trouble.

1604
01:14:21,260 --> 01:14:22,590
No, we had to turn them
away at the door.

1605
01:14:22,600 --> 01:14:23,730
Didn't we, dear?

1606
01:14:23,730 --> 01:14:24,860
- Thanks.
- Oh.

1607
01:14:24,860 --> 01:14:27,030
- Gene.
- Mrs. Graham.

1608
01:14:27,030 --> 01:14:29,270
So, everything okay?

1609
01:14:29,270 --> 01:14:32,540
Uh, it's gotten pretty hot
over at Ben's house.

1610
01:14:32,540 --> 01:14:34,940
Oh, things are
not going well?

1611
01:14:34,940 --> 01:14:38,810
No. Ben and Mr. Beebe
are at real loggerheads.

1612
01:14:38,810 --> 01:14:40,880
Fritz and Ben
on opposite sides?

1613
01:14:40,880 --> 01:14:41,980
I made a commitment
to publish these papers.

1614
01:14:41,980 --> 01:14:43,280
Excuse me. Pardon me.

1615
01:14:43,280 --> 01:14:45,020
The whole staff will revolt,
if we don't publish.

1616
01:14:45,020 --> 01:14:47,550
<font color="#138ce9">ANTHONY:</font> Meg, I hardly think
people are gonna resign.

1617
01:14:47,550 --> 01:14:48,690
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> Enjoying the fight?

1618
01:14:48,690 --> 01:14:50,090
<font color="#138ce9">TONY:</font> Yeah, who's winning?

1619
01:14:50,090 --> 01:14:52,190
- Nixon.
- I didn't see him come in.

1620
01:14:52,190 --> 01:14:55,130
Really? He's got his hand
so far up Fritz's ass.

1621
01:14:56,500 --> 01:14:57,900
Where is Fritz?

1622
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:02,670
<font color="#138ce9">ANTHONY:</font> That is not at all
what I'm saying. No.

1623
01:15:02,670 --> 01:15:04,540
<font color="#138ce9">MEG:</font> Not in so many words,
but you're a bunch of lawyers.

1624
01:15:04,540 --> 01:15:05,400
Will you cut through the shit!

1625
01:15:05,410 --> 01:15:06,770
<font color="#138ce9">ANTHONY:</font> Is the profanity necessary?

1626
01:15:06,770 --> 01:15:07,870
If we're not gonna publish,

1627
01:15:07,880 --> 01:15:09,840
why are we busting
our rear ends, Ben?

1628
01:15:09,840 --> 01:15:11,610
Just keep writing.

1629
01:15:11,610 --> 01:15:12,910
<font color="#ff00ff">(STUTTERS)</font>

1630
01:15:12,910 --> 01:15:15,280
Can you stop
playing <i>Chopsticks?</i>

1631
01:15:15,280 --> 01:15:17,650
<font color="#138ce9">BAGDIKIAN:</font> We're not gonna get it wrong!

1632
01:15:20,190 --> 01:15:22,060
What's up there, Fritz?

1633
01:15:22,590 --> 01:15:24,920
Calling Kay.

1634
01:15:24,930 --> 01:15:27,990
I'm sorry, Ben.
I know you want this.

1635
01:15:28,000 --> 01:15:30,600
There will be another one.

1636
01:15:30,600 --> 01:15:32,960
Like hell there will be.

1637
01:15:32,970 --> 01:15:34,800
<font color="#138ce9">ROGER:</font> Given the
sensitive circumstances...

1638
01:15:34,800 --> 01:15:36,400
<font color="#138ce9">PHIL:</font> Sensitive circumstances?
Really?

1639
01:15:36,400 --> 01:15:38,070
<font color="#138ce9">ROGER:</font> How would you describe it?

1640
01:15:38,070 --> 01:15:41,040
<font color="#138ce9">MURREY:</font> Uh, well,
we're trying to make a story.

1641
01:15:41,040 --> 01:15:43,580
<font color="#138ce9">FRITZ:</font> <i>Hello. Hello, I'm
making a telephone call.</i>

1642
01:15:43,580 --> 01:15:45,380
Yeah, well, it's my house.

1643
01:15:45,380 --> 01:15:48,080
- So I'll be on the call.
- <i>All right, Ben.</i>

1644
01:15:48,080 --> 01:15:52,720
I just want to thank you all
for coming out this evening...

1645
01:15:52,720 --> 01:15:55,650
to help me launch
Harry Gladstein...

1646
01:15:55,660 --> 01:15:57,820
and his new sailboat...

1647
01:15:57,830 --> 01:16:00,260
into the Chesapeake Bay.

1648
01:16:01,860 --> 01:16:05,430
And into his
very well earned retirement.

1649
01:16:05,430 --> 01:16:07,530
Let me just tell you
a little bit about

1650
01:16:07,540 --> 01:16:09,940
why I'm so wild about Harry.

1651
01:16:09,940 --> 01:16:12,940
Mrs. Graham.
It's Mr. Beebe on the phone.

1652
01:16:12,940 --> 01:16:16,010
In 1949, wasn't it?

1653
01:16:16,010 --> 01:16:19,680
Uh, Phil Graham first brought
Harry to the company.

1654
01:16:19,680 --> 01:16:22,650
- I'm afraid they need you now.
- And I remember, he told me...

1655
01:16:22,650 --> 01:16:23,950
Mrs. Graham.

1656
01:16:23,950 --> 01:16:25,550
<font color="#ff00ff">(WHISPERS)</font> They need you now.

1657
01:16:26,820 --> 01:16:27,890
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1658
01:16:27,890 --> 01:16:31,190
Oh, dear. I'm so sorry.

1659
01:16:31,190 --> 01:16:33,120
- Forgive me, Harry.
-<font color="#138ce9"> HARRY:</font> Yeah.

1660
01:16:33,130 --> 01:16:35,090
<font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font>
I think I'll have to suspend.

1661
01:16:35,090 --> 01:16:37,430
Well, you're paying
the overtime.

1662
01:16:37,430 --> 01:16:39,800
- <font color="#ff00ff">(ALL LAUGH)</font>
- I'll be right back.

1663
01:16:39,800 --> 01:16:41,540
I'm so sorry, Mrs. Graham.

1664
01:16:41,900 --> 01:16:43,370
Yeah.

1665
01:16:43,370 --> 01:16:44,640
We should wait.

1666
01:16:44,640 --> 01:16:48,380
Yeah, I understand, Ben,
but if you wait a day...

1667
01:16:49,480 --> 01:16:52,210
- Fritz on the phone for me?
- We should be on this call.

1668
01:16:52,210 --> 01:16:54,550
Well, there's an extension
in the living room.

1669
01:16:54,550 --> 01:16:57,620
Liz, show them where, please?
Thank you.

1670
01:17:07,800 --> 01:17:09,030
Hello, Fritz?

1671
01:17:09,030 --> 01:17:11,430
Hello, Kay. Would you like me
to catch you up?

1672
01:17:11,430 --> 01:17:12,770
I say we can,
he says we can't.

1673
01:17:12,770 --> 01:17:13,900
There, you're caught up.

1674
01:17:13,900 --> 01:17:15,530
- <font color="#138ce9">FRITZ:</font> <i>Ben...</i>
- <font color="#138ce9">ARTHUR:</font> <i>Hello, it's Art.</i>

1675
01:17:15,540 --> 01:17:18,270
<i>Well, Ben,
there are concerns here</i>

1676
01:17:18,270 --> 01:17:20,300
<i>that are frankly
above your pay grade.</i>

1677
01:17:20,310 --> 01:17:22,040
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> <i>Well, there's
a few above yours, Art,</i>

1678
01:17:22,040 --> 01:17:23,410
<i>like fucking freedom
of the press.</i>

1679
01:17:23,410 --> 01:17:25,310
Let's just be civil if we can.

1680
01:17:25,310 --> 01:17:27,340
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> <i>Do you think
Nixon is going to be civil?</i>

1681
01:17:27,350 --> 01:17:30,080
He is trying to censor the
goddamn <i>New York Times.</i>

1682
01:17:30,080 --> 01:17:31,820
Yes, <i>The Times</i>, not <i>The Post.</i>

1683
01:17:31,820 --> 01:17:33,450
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> <i>It's the same damn thing.</i>

1684
01:17:33,450 --> 01:17:37,420
<i>This is an historic fight.
If they lose, we lose.</i>

1685
01:17:37,420 --> 01:17:39,290
<font color="#138ce9">PAUL:</font> <i>Hello? Is someone
on the phone?</i>

1686
01:17:39,290 --> 01:17:40,730
<font color="#138ce9">PHIL:</font> <i>This is Phil.</i>

1687
01:17:40,730 --> 01:17:42,360
Is that Phil Geyelin?

1688
01:17:42,360 --> 01:17:44,600
<font color="#138ce9">PHIL:</font> <i>Uh, yes, Mrs. Graham.</i>

1689
01:17:44,600 --> 01:17:47,170
Good. I'd like you to weigh in
if you would...

1690
01:17:47,170 --> 01:17:48,370
because I wanna know

1691
01:17:48,370 --> 01:17:50,500
what the staff
is feeling about this.

1692
01:17:50,500 --> 01:17:53,270
<font color="#138ce9">PHIL:</font> <i>Uh, well,
frankly Mrs. Graham...</i>

1693
01:17:53,270 --> 01:17:55,270
<i>Ben Bagdikian and Chal Roberts</i>

1694
01:17:55,280 --> 01:17:58,010
<i>have, uh, both
threatened to resign...</i>

1695
01:17:58,010 --> 01:18:00,180
<i>if we don't publish, that is.</i>

1696
01:18:00,180 --> 01:18:01,650
Come on, Kay,
what do you expect?

1697
01:18:01,650 --> 01:18:02,510
<i>They got nothing to lose.</i>

1698
01:18:02,520 --> 01:18:04,120
Due respect,
we all have everything

1699
01:18:04,120 --> 01:18:05,520
to lose if we don't publish.

1700
01:18:05,520 --> 01:18:08,390
What will happen to the
reputation of this paper?

1701
01:18:08,390 --> 01:18:10,590
Everyone will find out
we had the study.

1702
01:18:10,590 --> 01:18:12,620
<i>Hell, I bet half the town
knows already.</i>

1703
01:18:12,630 --> 01:18:14,790
<i>What will it look like
if we sit on our asses?</i>

1704
01:18:14,800 --> 01:18:16,400
It'll look like
we were prudent.

1705
01:18:16,400 --> 01:18:18,130
<font color="#138ce9">BEN:</font> <i>It will look like
we were afraid!</i>

1706
01:18:18,130 --> 01:18:21,270
We will lose! The country
will lose! Nixon wins!

1707
01:18:21,270 --> 01:18:23,130
Nixon wins this one,
and the next one...

1708
01:18:23,140 --> 01:18:25,100
and all the ones after that,
because we were scared.

1709
01:18:25,100 --> 01:18:26,370
Because the only way to assert

1710
01:18:26,370 --> 01:18:28,640
the right to publish
is to publish.

1711
01:18:29,640 --> 01:18:31,810
<font color="#ff00ff">(BREATHES DEEPLY)</font>

1712
01:18:33,450 --> 01:18:34,650
Fritz.

1713
01:18:34,650 --> 01:18:36,850
<font color="#ff00ff">(STUTTERS)</font> Is Fritz there?

1714
01:18:38,680 --> 01:18:41,090
Fritz, are you on?

1715
01:18:41,090 --> 01:18:43,090
<font color="#138ce9">FRITZ:</font> <i>I'm here, Kay.</i>

1716
01:18:45,860 --> 01:18:48,100
What do you think?

1717
01:18:49,360 --> 01:18:52,530
What do you think I should do?

1718
01:18:53,000 --> 01:18:54,530
<font color="#ff00ff">(FRITZ SIGHS)</font>

1719
01:18:54,540 --> 01:18:56,500
<font color="#138ce9">FRITZ:</font> <i>I think...</i>

1720
01:18:56,500 --> 01:18:59,440
<i>there are arguments
on both sides.</i>

1721
01:18:59,440 --> 01:19:00,440
Yeah.

1722
01:19:02,940 --> 01:19:05,150
But I guess
I wouldn't publish.

1723
01:19:21,660 --> 01:19:23,500
<font color="#ff00ff">(BREATHING HEAVILY)</font>

1724
01:19:28,140 --> 01:19:30,540
<font color="#ff00ff">(STUTTERS)</font> Let's go.
Let's do it.

1725
01:19:30,540 --> 01:19:34,770
Let's go. Let's go, let's go.
Let's publish.

1726
01:19:38,880 --> 01:19:40,610
- What?
- Phil?

1727
01:19:40,610 --> 01:19:42,280
What'd she say?

1728
01:19:42,950 --> 01:19:44,520
We go.

1729
01:19:46,220 --> 01:19:48,290
She says, we publish.

1730
01:19:48,290 --> 01:19:49,350
<font color="#ff00ff">(BAGDIKIAN SIGHS)</font>

1731
01:19:49,360 --> 01:19:50,420
- Hot damn.
- My God.

1732
01:19:50,420 --> 01:19:52,220
- Holy shit.
- Let's get this out.

1733
01:19:52,230 --> 01:19:54,190
- Holy shit.
- <font color="#ff00ff">(TYPING)</font>

1734
01:19:54,190 --> 01:19:55,460
- I need that, Meg.
-<font color="#138ce9"> MEG:</font> Sorry.

1735
01:19:55,460 --> 01:19:56,730
Whoa, whoa, whoa!
Hold your horses.

1736
01:19:56,730 --> 01:19:57,960
- I need the notes!
- Sorry.

1737
01:19:57,970 --> 01:19:59,330
- How many pages is it?
- 13.

1738
01:19:59,330 --> 01:20:00,970
We got two hours to get it
to the composing room.

1739
01:20:00,970 --> 01:20:03,130
<font color="#138ce9">CHALMERS:</font> I got it! Almost!
Wait one moment. I'm typing.

1740
01:20:03,140 --> 01:20:04,600
<font color="#138ce9">BAGDIKIAN:</font> All right.

1741
01:20:05,570 --> 01:20:06,910
- Wait, wait, wait.
- Who's taking it?

1742
01:20:06,910 --> 01:20:08,070
I got it.

1743
01:20:08,080 --> 01:20:09,240
Call National desk.

1744
01:20:09,240 --> 01:20:10,880
Tell them Bagdikian
is coming with the story.

1745
01:20:10,880 --> 01:20:12,210
Done!

1746
01:20:12,210 --> 01:20:13,980
All right.
Get it in the paper.

1747
01:20:13,980 --> 01:20:15,480
Editorial meeting.

1748
01:20:15,480 --> 01:20:18,050
- Ben?
- Yeah? Thanks.

1749
01:20:18,050 --> 01:20:20,320
<font color="#138ce9">HOWARD:</font> Good job, Murrey.

1750
01:20:20,320 --> 01:20:21,920
<font color="#ff00ff">(ELEVATOR DINGS)</font>

1751
01:20:26,830 --> 01:20:29,090
- That it?
- That's it.

1752
01:20:29,100 --> 01:20:31,200
<font color="#ff00ff">(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)</font>

1753
01:20:39,240 --> 01:20:41,680
You... You got half an hour.

1754
01:20:52,620 --> 01:20:55,120
I'm not sure how much thought

1755
01:20:55,120 --> 01:20:56,820
you've put
into this decision...

1756
01:20:56,820 --> 01:20:57,760
but we still have time.

1757
01:20:57,760 --> 01:20:59,590
The print deadline
is not 'til midnight.

1758
01:20:59,590 --> 01:21:01,730
I know when the
print deadline is.

1759
01:21:01,730 --> 01:21:03,700
Look, I'm still learning
how to do this,

1760
01:21:03,700 --> 01:21:05,300
but everything
I know about business...

1761
01:21:05,300 --> 01:21:07,800
tells me you're making
a serious mistake here.

1762
01:21:07,800 --> 01:21:09,670
One that will cost you
and your paper dearly,

1763
01:21:09,670 --> 01:21:11,670
and hurt every person
gathered here.

1764
01:21:11,670 --> 01:21:14,440
Not to mention, the hundreds
of others who work for you.

1765
01:21:14,440 --> 01:21:16,440
I'm just trying to put
my thoughts together.

1766
01:21:16,440 --> 01:21:19,010
Kay, all I want is
what is best

1767
01:21:19,010 --> 01:21:20,950
for you and your business.

1768
01:21:20,950 --> 01:21:23,850
But I just got off the phone
with a couple of bankers...

1769
01:21:23,850 --> 01:21:26,990
and they think it's possible,
likely even...

1770
01:21:26,990 --> 01:21:29,620
that a number of their
institutional investors...

1771
01:21:29,620 --> 01:21:31,720
will pull out
if you go ahead and publish.

1772
01:21:31,720 --> 01:21:35,260
- And if they pull out, Kay...
- <font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1773
01:21:36,200 --> 01:21:38,600
You got a couple of hours.

1774
01:21:39,030 --> 01:21:40,270
For your sake,

1775
01:21:40,270 --> 01:21:42,430
and for the sake of every one
of your employees...

1776
01:21:42,440 --> 01:21:44,370
I hope you will reconsider.

1777
01:21:51,780 --> 01:21:53,510
Give me the canister.

1778
01:21:59,090 --> 01:22:00,250
Get it downstairs...

1779
01:22:00,250 --> 01:22:02,120
and I want the page editor
standing over Lino

1780
01:22:02,120 --> 01:22:03,660
'til they got it
ready to print.

1781
01:22:03,660 --> 01:22:04,660
Okay.

1782
01:22:05,890 --> 01:22:07,160
<font color="#ff00ff">(AIR HISSES)</font>

1783
01:22:07,160 --> 01:22:08,230
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1784
01:22:08,230 --> 01:22:09,960
<font color="#138ce9">ROGER:</font> Mr. Bagdikian.

1785
01:22:15,240 --> 01:22:17,700
I need to know your source.

1786
01:22:17,700 --> 01:22:20,440
I thought I was clear earlier.

1787
01:22:20,440 --> 01:22:22,770
Well, we weren't
going to press earlier.

1788
01:22:22,780 --> 01:22:25,540
Yeah, well,
my answer's the same.

1789
01:22:25,550 --> 01:22:27,580
"This action has been
commenced to enjoin

1790
01:22:27,580 --> 01:22:29,410
<i>"The New York Times</i>
and their agents...

1791
01:22:29,420 --> 01:22:31,220
"from further
disseminating or disclosing

1792
01:22:31,220 --> 01:22:32,620
"certain alleged
top secret documents."

1793
01:22:32,620 --> 01:22:34,690
Are you trying
to piss me off?

1794
01:22:34,690 --> 01:22:36,520
No. Not me.
Judge Gurfein.

1795
01:22:36,520 --> 01:22:38,460
If you look at the text
of his restraining order...

1796
01:22:38,460 --> 01:22:40,560
I read his restraining order.

1797
01:22:40,560 --> 01:22:42,560
So then you know that if
<i>The Times</i> was your source...

1798
01:22:42,560 --> 01:22:44,230
we would be in
direct violation...

1799
01:22:44,230 --> 01:22:47,170
I did not get the study
from <i>The Times.</i>

1800
01:22:47,170 --> 01:22:48,370
You're sure?

1801
01:22:49,200 --> 01:22:50,770
We done?

1802
01:22:54,270 --> 01:22:56,740
Did you get it
from their source?

1803
01:23:03,680 --> 01:23:05,120
Excuse me?

1804
01:23:08,020 --> 01:23:10,120
Did you get the study

1805
01:23:10,120 --> 01:23:12,790
from the same source
as <i>The Times?</i>

1806
01:23:15,130 --> 01:23:18,600
We do not reveal
our sources.

1807
01:23:18,600 --> 01:23:20,630
"This action has been
commenced to enjoin

1808
01:23:20,630 --> 01:23:22,500
<i>"The New York Times</i>
and its agents..."

1809
01:23:22,500 --> 01:23:24,100
I get it!
I get it!

1810
01:23:27,640 --> 01:23:30,010
If you got the study
from the same source

1811
01:23:30,010 --> 01:23:31,740
that would
amount to collusion.

1812
01:23:31,750 --> 01:23:34,850
Yeah, we could
all be executed at dawn.

1813
01:23:35,850 --> 01:23:38,980
And we could be held
in contempt of court...

1814
01:23:38,990 --> 01:23:42,720
which means Mr. Bradlee and
Mrs. Graham could go to jail.

1815
01:23:44,720 --> 01:23:46,420
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1816
01:23:46,430 --> 01:23:48,460
Mr. Bagdikian...

1817
01:23:49,460 --> 01:23:52,930
how likely is it
that your source...

1818
01:23:52,930 --> 01:23:55,840
and <i>The Times</i> source
are the same person?

1819
01:23:57,440 --> 01:23:59,440
It's likely.

1820
01:24:00,940 --> 01:24:02,610
How likely?

1821
01:24:03,740 --> 01:24:04,880
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

1822
01:24:04,880 --> 01:24:06,680
Very.

1823
01:24:06,680 --> 01:24:08,750
- It's very likely.
- Yes.

1824
01:24:19,890 --> 01:24:22,060
What is all this?

1825
01:24:22,060 --> 01:24:24,860
Lemonade earnings.

1826
01:24:24,860 --> 01:24:28,100
Marina wanted me to
put it away for safekeeping.

1827
01:24:28,100 --> 01:24:29,440
Oh, wow.

1828
01:24:34,140 --> 01:24:35,980
We're publishing.

1829
01:24:39,680 --> 01:24:40,810
Wow.

1830
01:24:43,380 --> 01:24:45,820
I didn't think Kay'd do it.

1831
01:24:48,460 --> 01:24:50,920
That's brave.

1832
01:24:50,920 --> 01:24:53,890
Well, she's not the only one
who's brave.

1833
01:24:53,890 --> 01:24:55,160
Oh. <font color="#ff00ff">(CHUCKLES)</font>

1834
01:24:55,160 --> 01:24:57,290
What have you got to lose?

1835
01:24:57,300 --> 01:24:59,030
Uh, my job.

1836
01:24:59,030 --> 01:25:00,430
My reputation.

1837
01:25:00,430 --> 01:25:02,140
Oh, Ben, please.

1838
01:25:03,300 --> 01:25:05,440
We both know
this will do nothing

1839
01:25:05,440 --> 01:25:08,440
but burnish your reputation.

1840
01:25:08,440 --> 01:25:10,310
And as for your job...

1841
01:25:10,310 --> 01:25:12,580
you can always
find another one.

1842
01:25:13,610 --> 01:25:16,850
Now, if you're trying to
make me feel better...

1843
01:25:16,850 --> 01:25:19,790
there's nicer ways
of doing it.

1844
01:25:21,220 --> 01:25:23,220
You're very brave.

1845
01:25:25,190 --> 01:25:27,830
But Kay...

1846
01:25:27,830 --> 01:25:32,360
Kay is in a position
she never thought she'd be in.

1847
01:25:32,370 --> 01:25:34,330
A position
I'm sure plenty of people

1848
01:25:34,330 --> 01:25:37,100
don't think she should have.

1849
01:25:37,100 --> 01:25:39,400
And when you're told
time and time again

1850
01:25:39,410 --> 01:25:41,470
that you're not good enough.

1851
01:25:41,470 --> 01:25:44,940
That your opinion
doesn't matter as much.

1852
01:25:44,940 --> 01:25:48,650
When they don't
just look past you.

1853
01:25:48,650 --> 01:25:52,580
When, to them,
you're not even there.

1854
01:25:52,590 --> 01:25:54,750
When that's been your
reality for so long...

1855
01:25:54,750 --> 01:25:57,790
it's hard not to let
yourself think it's true.

1856
01:25:58,760 --> 01:26:01,990
So, to make this decision...

1857
01:26:02,000 --> 01:26:04,730
to risk her fortune
and the company

1858
01:26:04,730 --> 01:26:07,200
that's been her entire life...

1859
01:26:08,540 --> 01:26:10,770
well, I think that's brave.

1860
01:26:12,610 --> 01:26:14,140
<font color="#ff00ff">(PHONE RINGS)</font>

1861
01:26:17,140 --> 01:26:18,010
Bradlee.

1862
01:26:18,010 --> 01:26:20,680
<font color="#138ce9">BAGDIKIAN:</font> <i>Ben, we got a problem.</i>

1863
01:26:31,220 --> 01:26:33,090
You remember this?

1864
01:26:34,960 --> 01:26:37,030
- The day before the funeral.
